# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] An **act of parliament**, as a form of primary legislation, is a text of law passed by the legislative body of a jurisdiction (often a parliament or council).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In most countries with a parliamentary system of government, acts of parliament begin as a bill, which the legislature votes on.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Depending on the structure of government, this text may then be subject to assent or approval from the executive branch.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] A draft act of parliament is known as a bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In other words, a bill is a proposed law that needs to be discussed in the parliament before it can become a law.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In territories with a Westminster system, most bills that have any possibility of becoming law are introduced into parliament by the government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] This will usually happen following the publication of a "white paper", setting out the issues and the way in which the proposed new law is intended to deal with them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] A bill may also be introduced into parliament without formal government backing; this is known as a private member's bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In territories with a multicameral parliament, most bills may be first introduced in any chamber.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] However, certain types of legislation are required, either by constitutional convention or by law, to be introduced into a specific chamber.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] For example, bills imposing a tax, or involving public expenditure, are introduced into the House of Commons in the United Kingdom, Canada's House of Commons, Lok Sabha of India and Ireland's Dáil as a matter of law.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Conversely, bills proposed by the Law Commission and consolidation bills traditionally start in the House of Lords.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Once introduced, a bill must go through a number of stages before it can become law.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In theory, this allows the bill's provisions to be debated in detail, and for amendments to the original bill to also be introduced, debated, and agreed to.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In bicameral parliaments, a bill that has been approved by the chamber into which it was introduced then sends the bill to the other chamber.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Broadly speaking, each chamber must separately agree to the same version of the bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Finally, the approved bill receives assent; in most territories this is merely a formality and is often a function exercised by the head of state.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In some countries, such as in France, Belgium, Luxembourg, Spain and Portugal, the term for a bill differs depending on whether it is initiated by the government (when it is known as a "draft"), or by the parliament (a "proposition", i.e., a private member's bill).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Second reading: As in the UK, the stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Again, the second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] A defeat for a government bill on this reading signifies a major loss.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Consideration in detail: This usually takes place on the floor of the House.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Generally, committees sit on the floor of the House and consider the bill in detail.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Very rarely do debates occur during this stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Representatives; to the House of Representatives, if it is a Senate bill), which may amend it.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are posted back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The State of Queensland's Parliament is unicameral and skips this and the rest of the stages.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Representatives amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu, or reject them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] However, the Senate may not amend money bills, though it can "request" the House to make amendments.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] A bill may pass backward and forward several times at this stage, as each House amends or rejects changes proposed by the other.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If each House insists on disagreeing with the other, the bill is lost.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: Often, when a bill cannot be passed in the same form by both Houses, it is "laid aside", i.e. abandoned.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In the federal Parliament, there is also a special constitutional procedure allowing the passage of the bill without the separate agreement of both houses.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the House twice passes the same bill, and the Senate twice fails to pass that bill (either through rejection or through the passage of unacceptable amendments), then the Governor-General may dissolve both Houses of Parliament simultaneously and call an election for the entire Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] After the election, if the House again passes the bill, but the deadlock between the Houses persists, then the Governor-General may convene a joint sitting of both Houses, where a final decision will be taken on the bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Although the House and the Senate sit as a single body, bills passed at a joint sitting are treated as if they had been passed by each chamber separately.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The procedure only applies if the bill originated in the House of Representatives.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Six double dissolutions have occurred, though a joint sitting was only held once, in 1974.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The bill is sent to the viceroy (the Governor-General for the Commonwealth; the governor for a state; the administrator for a territory) for royal assent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Acts in the Australian Capital Territory do not require this step.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Second reading: This stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the bill is read a second time, then it progresses to the committee stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a standing committee of the Commons or Senate.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Report stage: this takes place on the floor of the appropriate chamber, and allows the House or Senate to approve amendments made in committee, or to propose new ones.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Senate bill), where it will face a virtually identical process.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are sent back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu or reject them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: There is no specific procedure to resolve a dispute between the houses.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Either house can amend or reject a bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The debate on each stage is actually debate on a specific motion.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] For the first reading, there is no debate.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In the Report stage, the debate is on the motions for specific amendments.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Once a bill has passed both Houses in an identical form, it is presented to the Governor General, who gives it royal assent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Although the Governor General can refuse to assent a bill, this power has never been exercised.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Bills being reviewed by Parliament are assigned numbers: 2 to 200 for government bills, 201 to 1000 for private member's bills, and 1001 up for private bills.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] They are preceded by C- if they originate in the House of Commons, or S- if they originate in the Senate.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] For example, Bill C-250 was a private member's bill introduced in the House.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Bills C-1 and S-1 are pro forma bills, and are introduced at the beginning of each session in order to assert the right of each Chamber to manage its own affairs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] They are introduced and read a first time, and then are dropped from the Order Paper.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Second reading – discussion stage: This stage consists of detailed consideration of the bill and proposed amendments.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Third reading – voting stage: This stage is confined only to arguments either in support of the bill or for its rejection as a whole, without referring to its details.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] After the bill is passed, it is sent to the other house.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Bill in the other house (Rajya Sabha): After a bill, other than a money bill, is transmitted to the other house, it goes through all the stages in that house as that in the first house.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] But if the bill passed by one house is amended by the other house, it goes back to the originating house.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] President's approval: When a bill is passed by both the houses, it is sent to the President for his approval.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The President can assent or withhold his assent to a bill or he can return a bill, other than a money bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the President gives his assent, the bill is published in *The Gazette of India* and becomes an Act from the date of his assent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If he withholds his assent, the bill is dropped, which is known as pocket veto.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The pocket veto is not written in the constitution and has only been exercised once, by President Zail Singh in 1986, over the postal act where the government wanted to open postal letters without warrant.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the president returns it for reconsideration, the Parliament must do so, but if it is passed again and returned to him, he must give his assent to it.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In the Irish Parliament, the Oireachtas, bills pass through the following stages.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Bills may be initiated in either the Dáil or the Seanad, and must pass both houses.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Second stage – this involves a discussion of the general principle of the bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] It is introduced by the sponsoring minister (or in the case of a private member's bill, by the member) and is followed by contributions from the floor of the house.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Finally, the debate is brought to a conclusion by voting on the proposal "that the bill now be read a second time".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Third stage, commonly referred to as the Committee Stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] This involves section by section scrutiny of the bill and any amendments which have been tabled.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In the Dáil this usually takes place in a committee room and will involve examination by one of the select committees.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In the Seanad, this stage takes place in the chamber.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The Seanad may only make recommendations rather than amendments, in the case of a money bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Fourth stage, commonly referred to as the Report Stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] At this point, a version of the bill incorporating any changes made at the Committee Stage is printed for consideration.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In both houses, this stage is taken on the floor of the chamber.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Amendments may be considered at this stage but must arise from matters discussed or changes made at the Committee Stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Fifth stage: in practice this is a formality, taken with the fourth stage and referred to as the Report and Final Stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Passage in the other house: the same stages are repeated in the other house and the bill is then deemed to have been passed, except that any bill initiated in the Dáil and amended by the Seanad must return to the Dáil for final consideration.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Signature: once the bill has passed both houses it is sent to the President for signature.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The signed copy is then enrolled in the Office of the Supreme Court.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Select committee stage: The bill is considered by a select committee, which scrutinises the bill in detail and hears public submissions on the matter.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The select committee may recommend amendments to the bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Second reading: The general principles of the bill are debated, and a vote is held.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is put before a Committee of the House.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Committee of the House: The bill is debated and voted on, clause by clause, by the whole House sitting as a committee.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Third reading: Summarising arguments are made, and a final vote is taken.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is passed to the Governor-General for royal assent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] New Zealand has no upper house, and so no further approval is necessary.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] A draft piece of legislation is called a *bill*; when this is passed by Parliament it becomes an *act* and part of statute law.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] There are two types of bill and act, *public* and *private*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Public acts apply to the whole of the UK or a number of its constituent countries – England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Private acts are local and personal in their effect, giving special powers to bodies such as local authorities or making exceptions to the law in particular geographic areas.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] First reading: This is a formality; no vote occurs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The bill is presented and ordered to be printed and, in the case of private members' bills, a date is set for second reading.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Second reading: A debate on the general principles of the bill is followed by a vote.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a public bill committee in the Commons and on the floor of the House in the Lords.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The committee considers each clause of the bill, and may make amendments to it.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Consideration (or report) stage: This takes place on the floor of the House, and is a further opportunity to amend the bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Unlike committee stage, the House need not consider every clause of the bill, only those to which amendments have been tabled.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended in the House of Lords.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Further amendments may be tabled at this stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Lords, if it originated in the Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Lords bill), which may amend it.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Lords/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: the bill is passed with any amendments and becomes an act of Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Stage one: The bill is considered by one or more of the subject committees of the parliament, which normally take evidence from the bill's promoter and other interested parties before reporting to the parliament on the principles of the bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Other committees, notably the Finance and Subordinate Legislation Committees, may also feed in at this stage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The report from the committee is followed by a debate in the full parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Stage two: The bill returns to the subject committee where it is subject to line-by-line scrutiny and amendment.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] This is similar to the committee stage in the UK Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Stage three: The bill as amended by the committee returns to the full parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] There is a further opportunity for amendment, followed by a debate on the whole bill, at the end of which the parliament decides whether to pass the bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: After the bill has been passed, the presiding officer submits it to the monarch for royal assent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] However, he cannot do so until a four-week period has elapsed during which the law officers of the Scottish government or the UK government can refer the bill to the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom for a ruling on whether it is within the powers of the parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] There are special procedures for emergency bills, member's bills (similar to private member's bills in the UK Parliament), committee bills, and private bills.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In Singapore, the bill passes through these certain stages before becoming into an Act of Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Second reading: In this stage, the bill is further discussed and put to a second vote.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If more than half of the votes are ayes the bill proceeds to the select committee.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Select committee: The select committee consists of people not only from the parliaments, but also the people who could be affected by the bill is passed into law.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] This is to ensure equality and that the bill is fair for all.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If the bill is in favour, it will proceed to the third reading.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Third reading: After the select committee has discussed and are in favour of the bill, they will put it to a vote.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] At this juncture, if the votes are more than half ayes, it will be sent to the President of Singapore.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] President Assent: The president must give permission in order for the bill to be passed.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] If they approve it, it will become a statute passed down by the members of parliament which is called an Act of Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Acts passed by the Parliament of England did not originally have titles, and could only be formally cited by reference to the parliamentary session in which they were passed, with each individual act being identified by year and chapter number.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Descriptive titles began to be added to the enrolled acts by the official clerks, as a reference aid; over time, titles came to be included within the text of each bill.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Since the mid-nineteenth century, it has also become common practice for acts to have a short title, as a convenient alternative to the sometimes lengthy main titles.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The Short Titles Act 1892, and its replacement the Short Titles Act 1896, gave short titles to many acts which previously lacked them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The numerical citation of acts has also changed over time.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The original method was based on the regnal year (or years) in which the relevant parliamentary session met.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] This has been replaced in most territories by simple reference to the calendar year, with the first act passed being chapter 1, and so on.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] In the United Kingdom, legislation has referenced by year and chapter number since 1963 (Acts of Parliament Numbering and Citation Act 1962).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Each act is numbered consecutively based on the date it received royal assent, for example the 43rd act passed in 1980 would be 1980 chapter 43.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] The full reference includes the (short) title and would be the Magistrate's Court Act 1980 (c.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/act-of-parliament] Until the 1980s, acts of the Australian state of Victoria were numbered in a continuous sequence from 1857; thus the Age of Majority Act 1977 was No.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] Common examples include ad hoc committees and commissions created at the national or international level for a specific task, and the term is often used to describe arbitration (ad hoc arbitration).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] Ad hoc can also function as an adjective describing temporary, provisional, or improvised methods to deal with a particular problem, the tendency of which has given rise to the noun *adhocism*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] This concept highlights the flexibility and adaptability often required in problem-solving across various domains.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] In everyday language, "ad hoc" is sometimes used informally to describe improvised or makeshift solutions, emphasizing their temporary nature and specific applicability to immediate circumstances.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] Style guides disagree on whether Latin phrases like ad hoc should be italicized.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] For example, *The Chicago Manual of Style* recommends that familiar Latin phrases that are listed in the *Webster's Dictionary*, including "ad hoc", not be italicized.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] In science and philosophy, ad hoc means the addition of extraneous hypotheses to a theory to save it from being falsified.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] Ad hoc hypotheses compensate for anomalies not anticipated by the theory in its unmodified form.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] Scientists are often skeptical of scientific theories that rely on frequent, unsupported adjustments to sustain them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] Ad hoc hypotheses are often characteristic of pseudo-scientific subjects such as homeopathy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] In the military, ad hoc units are created during unpredictable situations, when the cooperation between different units is suddenly needed for fast action, or from remnants of previous units which have been overrun or otherwise whittled down.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] In national and sub-national governance, ad hoc bodies may be established to deal with specific problems not easily accommodated by the current structure of governance or to address multi-faceted issues spanning several areas of governance.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] In the UK and other commonwealth countries, ad hoc Royal Commissions may be set up to address specific questions as directed by parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] In diplomacy, diplomats may be appointed by a government as special envoys, or diplomats who serve on an ad hoc basis due to the possibility that such envoys' offices may either not be retained by a future government or may only exist during the duration of a relevant cause.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/ad-hoc] The term *ad hoc networking* typically refers to a system of network elements that combine to form a network requiring little or no planning.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Noted for its close association with the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party, Adani was the largest Indian conglomerate as of 2022 with a US$206 billion market capitalisation, surpassing Tata Group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] It lost more than $104 billion in value after fraud and market manipulation allegations by short-seller firm Hindenburg Research.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In May 2024, the Adani Group's market capitalisation returned to over $200 billion after the Supreme Court directed the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) to expedite its investigation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani Exports Limited started as a commodity trading company in 1988 and expanded into importing and exporting multiple commodities.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] With a capital of ₹5 lakhs, the company was established as a partnership firm with the flagship company Adani Enterprises, previously Adani Exports.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 1990, the Adani Group developed its own port in Mundra to provide a base for its trading operations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] It began construction at Mundra in 1995.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 1998, it became the top net foreign exchange earner for India Inc.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The company began coal trading in 1999, followed by a joint venture in edible oil refining in 2000 with the formation of Adani Wilmar.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani handled 4 Mt of cargo at Mundra in 2002, becoming the largest private port in India.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Later in 2006, the company became the largest coal importer in India with 11 Mt of coal handling.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The company expanded its business in 2008, purchasing Bunyu Mine in Indonesia which has 180 Mt of coal reserves.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2009 the firm began generating 330 MW of thermal power.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] It also built an edible oil refining capacity in India of 2.2 Mt per annum.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The Adani group became India's largest private coal mining company after Adani Enterprises won the Orissa mine rights in 2010.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Operations at the Port of Dahej commenced in 2011 and its capacity subsequently grew to 20 Mt.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The company also bought Galilee Basin mine in Australia with 10.4 gigatonnes (Gt) of coal reserves.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] More than 60 per cent of the Adani Group's revenue is derived from coal-related businesses.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2011, the Adani group also bought Abbot Point port in Australia with 50 Mt of handling capacity.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] It commissioned India's largest solar power plant with a capacity 40 MW.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] As the firm achieved 3,960 MW capacity, it became the largest private sector thermal power producer in India.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2012 The company shifted its focus on three business clusters – resources, logistics and energy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani Power emerged as India's largest private power producer in 2014.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani Power's total installed capacity then stood at 9,280 MW.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 16 May of the same year, Adani Ports acquired Dhamra Port on East coast of India for ₹5,500 crore (equivalent to ₹88 billion or US$920 million in 2023).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Dhamra Port was a 50:50 joint venture between Tata Steel and L&T Infrastructure Development Projects, which has been acquired by Adani Ports.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The port began operations in May 2011 and handled a total cargo of 14.3 Mt in 2013–14.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] With the acquisition of Dhamra Port, the group is planning to increase its capacity to over 200 Mt by 2020.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2015, the Adani Group's Adani Renewable Energy Park signed a pact with the Rajasthan Government for a 50:50 joint venture to set up India's largest solar park with a capacity of 10,000 MW.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In November 2015, the Adani group began construction at the port in Vizhinjam, Kerala.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani Aero Defence signed a pact with the Israeli arms manufacturer, Elbit-ISTAR, and Alpha Design Technologies to work in the field of Unmanned Aircraft Systems (UAS) in India in 2016.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In April, Adani Enterprises secured approval from the Government of Gujarat to begin work on building a solar power equipment plant.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In September, Adani Green Energy (Tamil Nadu), the renewable wing of the Adani Group, began operations in Kamuthi in Ramanathapuram, Tamil Nadu with a capacity of 648 MW at an estimated cost of ₹4,550 crore (equivalent to ₹65 billion or US$680 million in 2023).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In the same month, the Adani Group inaugurated a 648 MW single-location solar power plant.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] It was the world's largest solar power plant at the time it was set up.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 22 December 2017, the Adani Group acquired the power arm of Reliance Infrastructure for ₹18,800 crore (US$2.89 billion).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In October 2019, French oil and gas company TotalEnergies bought a 37.4% stake in Adani Gas for ₹6,155 crore (US$874.04 million) and obtained joint control of the company.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Total also invested US$510 million in a subsidiary of Adani Green Energy in February 2020.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In August 2020, Adani Group obtained a majority stake in Mumbai and Navi Mumbai airports after entering a debt acquisition agreement with GVK Group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Through a concession agreement with the Airports Authority of India, Adani Group also obtained a 50-year lease on Ahmedabad, Guwahati, Jaipur, Lucknow, Mangalore and Thiruvananthapuram airports.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In May 2021, Adani Green Energy acquired SB Energy, a joint venture of SoftBank Group and Bharti Enterprises, for US$3.5 billion.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In May 2022, the Adani Group acquired Ambuja Cements and ACC for $10.5 billion.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The deal will make the Adani Group the second largest cement maker in India.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In May 2022, UAE-based conglomerate International Holding Company (IHC), headed by Syed Basar Shueb, invested US$2 billion in three Adani Group companies, namely Adani Green Energy, Adani Transmission and Adani Enterprises.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In June 2022, TotalEnergies acquired a 25% stake in Adani New Industries, the newly formed green hydrogen subsidiary of Adani Enterprises, for US$12.5 billion.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In May 2025, Adani Group abruptly ended its partnership with China-based lounge provider DragonPass, days after announcing it, stating DragonPass users would no longer access Adani airport lounges, with no impact on other customers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The Adani Group launched in 2014, with the support of the Australian and Queensland Governments, a mining and rail project, the Carmichael coal mine, in Queensland's Galilee Basin, for $21.5 billion over the life of the project, i.e.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Its annual capacity would be 10 Mt of thermal coal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In response to pressure by environmental activists, some international banks refused to finance it.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The mine has drawn criticism for its environmental impacts on the Great Barrier Reef, water usage, and carbon emissions, leading to a campaign known as Stop Adani, which put pressure on the Big Four banks in Australia not to finance the mine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In November 2018, Adani Australia announced that the Carmichael project would be 100% financed by Adani Group resources.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2015, the then-head of Adani's Australian mining division came under scrutiny due to his association with a mining pollution incident in Zambia, sparking renewed concerns about Adani's suitability to manage the Carmichael coal mine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] According to a collaborative report from Environmental Justice Australia, Jeyakumar Janakaraj held significant positions at a mining company that faced criminal charges related to the contamination of the Kafue River in Zambia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This occurred before he assumed leadership role of Adani's operations in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Specifically, Janakaraj served as the operations director at Konkola Copper Mines in 2010, when the company faced legal charges concerning the discharge of hazardous wastewater into the river.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In July 2019, the project received its final approvals from the government, and construction of the mine commenced.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2020, Adani Mining changed its name to Bravus Mining and Resources.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 29 December 2021, Bravus announced that the first shipment of high-quality coal from the Carmichael mine had been assembled at the North Queensland Export Terminal (NQXT) in Bowen ready for export as planned.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Chairman and MD Gautam Adani has been described as being close to former Chief Minister of Gujarat and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi and his ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This has led to allegations of cronyism as his firms have won many Indian energy and infrastructure government contracts.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2012, an Indian government audit accused Modi of giving low cost fuel from a Gujarat state-run gas company to the Adani group and other companies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In Jharkhand, the BJP-led state government made an exception to its energy policy for Adani's Godda power plant.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Both the Adani Group and Modi's government have denied allegations of cronyism.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The *Forbes Asia* noted that Adani Group has over the years leased almost 7,350 hectares of land from the government for the amount as small as " one U.S. cent a square meter (the rate maxed out at 45 cents a square meter).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] He in turn has sublet this land to other companies, including state-owned Indian Oil Co., for as much as $11 a square meter".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Between 2005 and 2007, Adani group acquired around 1200 hectares of land meant for grazing (gauchar) from the villagers for Adani SEZ.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In Kutch, Adani group acquired 930,770 square meters of land from the villagers for 19 cents per square meter for its power plant leading to significant environmental damage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Villagers living in Adani SEZ alleged that the land was signed off by village chiefs without their knowledge.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani group's subsidiary, Adani Ports & SEZ currently operates 15 ports across all Indian states.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The Adani group controls seven airports in India, six of which were acquired for 50 years in a bid after an alleged change of rules by the Modi government that had disallowed the group from bidding.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Most Adani Group projects outside of India were announced after Narendra Modi's visits to said countries or meetings with their heads of state.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2021, after a meeting with Modi, Sri Lankan President Gotabaya Rajapaksa told an official from the electricity board that Modi had pressured him to transfer a wind energy project to the Adani Group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] After Modi's visit to Bangladesh, the Bangladeshi government under Sheikh Hasina signed a deal with the Adani Group to import electricity from Jharkhand.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The opposition later argued that the deal was signed under pressure from the Modi government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The deal is currently under scrutiny of Bangladesh's interim government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] A report by The Washington Post revealed that in May 2025, India’s state insurer LIC India proposed investing $3.9 billion in Adani shares.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Subsequently, LIC invested $585 million in Adani Ports when the company needed to pay off its existing debt.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This move highlighted Adani’s influence within India’s Modi government and was criticized as a misuse of public funds.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The company's corporate debt totalled $30 billion in 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In August 2022, CreditSights, a unit of Fitch Ratings, warned that Adani's recent aggressive expansion had hurt the group's cash flow and credit metrics.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] It also stated that a potential "worst-case scenario" could lead the group to end up in a debt trap and a potential default.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The CreditSights report garnered significant attention for its dire assessment of Adani's "deeply overleveraged" book; after outreach by Adani, CreditSights softened its language but kept its main conclusion.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2007, the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) prohibited multiple Adani companies from engaging in the purchase or sale of securities for a period of two years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This action was taken due to their involvement in a manipulation scheme that occurred between 1999 and 2001 to artificially influence stock prices.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This manipulation was carried out through entities overseen by Ketan Parekh, the stockbroker who was the main accused in India's biggest stock market scandal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] After paying a fine of $140,000, the companies were eventually permitted to recommence their trading activities.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In March 2023, Adani group won a bid for the coal block North West of Madheri, where the only other bidder was Cavill Mining Private Limited, a minimum of two bidders are required for the first time auction of a commercial mine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] According to an investigation by Scroll.in, Cavill Mining Private Limited is the main promoter of Adicorp Enterprises.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adicorp Enterprises has also been alleged by Hindenburg to have funnelled funds between Adani companies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This has raised concerns of bid rigging and collusion.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani group also faced accusations of bid-rigging by the Indian National Congress after winning a contract to supply 6,600 MW of electricity to Maharashtra.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 27 February 2010, Central Bureau of Investigation arrested Rajesh Adani, managing director of Adani Enterprises Ltd., on charges of custom duty evasion amounting to ₹80 lakh.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Paranjoy Guha Thakurta, an Indian journalist working for the Economic and Political Weekly, co-authored an article about the Adani Group's tax evasion following which Adani Power sent a legal notice to the Economic and Political Weekly.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Fearing an expensive lawsuit by one of India's biggest corporate houses EPW then decided to take down the article, prompting Paranjoy Guha Thakurta's resignation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In August 2017, Indian customs alleged the Adani Group was diverting millions of funds from the company's books to Adani family tax havens overseas.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani was accused of using a Dubai shell company to divert the funds.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The details of a $235 million diversion were obtained and published by *The Guardian*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2014, the Directorate of Revenue Intelligence (DRI) mapped out a complex money trail from India through South Korea and Dubai, and eventually to an offshore company in Mauritius allegedly owned by Vinod Shantilal Adani, the older brother of Gautam Adani.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Same year, DRI forwarded a letter to the then SEBI chairperson,U.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Sinha, along with a CD containing evidence suggesting the improper diversion of Rs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Additionally, they provided two investigative notes, cautioning that the group might be involved in manipulating the stock market through funds allegedly siphoned off using the strategy of overvaluing power equipment imports.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] However, SEBI did not publicly acknowledge the receipt of this letter and the accompanying evidence from DRI until September 2023, when it was disclosed before the Supreme Court of India.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Between December 2021 and November 2023, Swiss authorities froze a total of $310 million in five different accounts linked to Adani group following investigations into money laundering.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On October 7 2025, Reuters reported that India’s DRI initiated an investigation into Adani Defence in March 2025 over alleged customs duty evasion totaling approximately ₹77 crore (US$8.0 million).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] According to two government sources and a document reviewed by Reuters, the case concerns the company’s alleged misclassification of certain missile components as exempt from import duties and taxes.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] According to Bloomberg News, the group has been found to be maintaining dubious business relations with an engineering contracting firm, Howe Engineering Projects.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This firm acquired the engineering business of PMC Project in 2016.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In the past, PMC Projects, an Adani contractor, was accused of inflating the value of imported power and infrastructure goods by nearly ₹1,500 crore.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Howe, now a separate entity, continues to work as an Adani contractor (just like PMC Projects) for major ports and railway lines being built in India.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Deloitte raised concerns in May 2023 about payments made by Adani's ports company to Howe, unable to determine whether Howe should be considered a related party.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Also, Adani Group had not publicly disclosed these payments until Deloitte highlighted them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In January 2023, Hindenburg Research published the findings of a two-year investigation alleging that Adani had engaged in market manipulation and accounting malpractices.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The report accused Adani of pulling "the largest con in corporate history" and "brazen stock manipulation and accounting fraud scheme over the course of decades".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Hindenburg also disclosed that it was holding short positions on Adani Group companies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Bonds and shares of companies associated with Adani experienced a decline of more than $104 billion in market value after the accusations, representing approximately half of the market value.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Hedge fund manager Bill Ackman said Hindenburg's Adani Report was "highly credible and extremely well researched." Adani denied the fraud allegations as without merit.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 1 February, Adani cancelled its planned $2.5 billion (Rs 20,000 crore) Follow-on Public Offer (FPO) citing market volatility, and announced that it would return the FPO money to investors.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Reserve Bank of India sought details from banks on exposure to Adani firms.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Citigroup's wealth unit stopped extending margin loans to its clients against securities of Adani Group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Credit Suisse Group AG stopped accepting bonds of Adani Group companies as collateral for margin loans to its private banking clients.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] S&P Dow Jones Indices removed Adani Enterprises from its sustainability index.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Norway's Oil Fund, which had already shed a bulk of its Adani shares pre-Hindenburg report, divested its entire stake following the report.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 19 May, on *prima facie*, a committee formed by the Supreme Court of India communicated its inability to conclude regarding the existence of a regulatory failure concerning the accusation of stock price manipulation by the group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This was primarily due to the insufficient information provided in the explanations by the SEBI's investigation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Earlier on 29 April, SEBI requested a six-month extension to conclude its investigation, instead of the initially given two months provided on 2 March.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] However, the Supreme Court granted a three-month extension and directed SEBI to complete the probe by 14 August 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 24 June 2023, Adani Group's share value took a significant dive, following reports that United States Department of Justice and US Securities and Exchange Commission were investigating the corporation's communications with its US-based investors, spurred by a report from a short seller.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 31 August 2023, Organised Crime and Corruption Reporting Project (OCCRP) put forth allegations asserting that a substantial amount of funds, in the hundreds of millions of dollars, were directed into publicly traded stocks of the Adani Group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] These investments purportedly occurred by means of investment funds situated in Mauritius, which are characterised as possessing a lack of transparency.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] These funds were reportedly associated with partners connected to the promoter family.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Supporting evidence presented in the report indicates that these entities engaged in protracted activities involving the acquisition and divestiture of Adani stock through offshore mechanisms, thereby concealing their active participation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This covert engagement apparently yielded significant financial gains.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Additionally, the documentation suggests that the overseeing investment firm compensated a company belonging to Vinod Adani for advisory services pertinent to their investment pursuits.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In October 2023, the National Financial Reporting Authority initiated an investigation, reaching out to several audit firms involved in examining the financial records of the Adani Group's listed companies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The Adani group also reported that the government was probing financial records of Mumbai International Airport and Navi Mumbai International Airport, both operated by the group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 3 January 2024, the Supreme Court ordered SEBI to complete its probe within 90 days (3 months), sparked by allegations from short-seller Hindenburg Research.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The Court dismissed requests for an SIT or CBI investigation and shifted focus to Hindenburg's conduct.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] After Hindenburg's allegations of fraud against the Adani group, GQG Partners LLC, an investment firm founded by Rajiv Jain purchased shares worth $4.6 billion in six Adani group subsidiaries.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In September 2024, GQG Partners was charged by the Securities and Exchange Commission for hindering whistleblower protections, through its restrictive Non-disclosure agreements that disallowed employees from reporting potential violations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Shares of the Adani Group fell sharply, with Adani Green Energy dropping 16% on 20 November 2024, after the US Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) alleged violations, including hindering whistleblower protections.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The allegations added to growing concerns over corporate governance within the conglomerate.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In July 2024, a whistleblower alleged that the Kenya Airports Authority had signed a $1.85 billion deal for the Adani Group to manage the Jomo Kenyatta International Airport for a period of 30 years in a build–operate–transfer move.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The alleged deal was brokered by ALG Global, a Spanish firm, and would be financed majorly by Kenyan taxpayers with full control of the airport granted to Adani Group for the 30 years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Following widespread protests, in September 2024, the Kenyan High Court temporarily suspended the proposal, to allow for judicial review.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The whistleblower, Nelson Amenya, fears for his life.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 16 September 2024, Adani group and Africa50 were given a $1.3 billion concession in a public-private partnership by the Kenyan government to build power transmission lines.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 25 October, Kenyan court suspended $736 million deal between Kenya Electrical Transmission Company and Adani Group's Adani Energy Solutions.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In October 2024, former Prime Minister of Kenya, Raila Odinga said he was introduced to Adani Group by Narendra Modi who organised a visit by Kenyan delegation to the projects of the company.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In November 2024, Kenya's President William Ruto has cancelled two significant deals with India's Adani Group: a lease agreement for Jomo Kenyatta International Airport, the country's main international airport, and a contract with the Kenya Electricity Transmission Company.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This announcement came during Ruto's state of the nation address, just a day after Adani's directors faced charges in a New York court for alleged bribery and fraud.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The airport deal, valued at $2.5 billion, involved a 30-year lease of JKIA and had been approved by the Kenya Airports Authority without public hearings.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Experts had advised conducting a public tender for such a significant agreement.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The proposal from Adani sought "favorable tax policies" from the Kenyan government, which raised concerns among critics.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The deal had sparked significant backlash, leading to anti-government protests and a strike by airport workers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Before the cancellation, President Ruto had dismissed reports about the airport deal as "fake news." Just a week prior, Kenya's transport cabinet secretary defended the Adani Group and the airport agreement in parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The cancellation has been welcomed by some Kenyans, including whistleblower Nelson Amenya, who views it as a victory for citizen empowerment and an indication that change is possible in the country.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2018, Adani Defence & Aerospace announced a joint venture with Elbit Systems, Israel's primary defence manufacturer, to produce Hermes 900 military drones in India.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In February 2024, 20 Hermes 900 drones were supplied to Israel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In April 2024, the Indian government under the BJP abstained from the UN vote calling for an arms embargo on Israel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This decision has been linked to Adani's military exports to Israel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] A February 2023 article in *The Signpost* said that the Adani team has been manipulating Wikipedia entries using sock puppet accounts to insert promotional material and remove or edit criticism.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In March 2024, the United States expanded its probe into Adani Group, particularly focusing on founder Gautam Adani's conduct and potential bribery by his group companies in exchange for favourable treatment regarding an energy project.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The investigation is being handled by the United States Attorney for the Eastern District of New York and the United States Department of Justice Criminal Division's fraud unit in Washington.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 20 November 2024, federal prosecutors in New York charged Gautam Adani and his associates with multiple counts of fraud, including bribing Indian government officials with over $250 million to secure solar energy contracts.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In March 2025, the Indian government initiated proceedings to deliver a US Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) summons to Gautam Adani concerning the alleged bribery scheme.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The summons requires Adani or his legal representative to appear in the US case.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] On 12 September 2024, the chief manufacturing officer of Ambuja Cement, a subsidiary of the Adani Group, was arrested over an alleged bribery attempt.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In January 2026, Adani group's shares fell down by 10%, incurring a loss of $12.5 billion, following SEC's request to the Indian court to issue email summons to the defendants in the bribery case.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] According to an investigation by the Financial Times, Adani group had imported $5 billion worth of coal at more than double the market prices through offshore intermediaries in Singapore, Taiwan and Dubai.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] A notice by Directorate of Revenue Intelligence also accused five Adani group companies of artificially inflating the value of imported coal from Indonesia by 50% to 100% in order to overcharge power companies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani group has also managed to block the release of documents to Indian government agencies for investigation in Singapore.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] A May 2024 investigation by OCCRP and *Financial Times* indicated that Adani Group fraudulently inflated the price of coal that it supplied to domestic utility companies, by falsifying low-grade coal as high-grade coal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In February 2025, it was revealed that the Adani Group paid £4 million to sponsor the green energy wing of London's Science Museum.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] This sponsorship faced criticism due to the company's involvement in coal mining and recent fraud allegations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In August 2022, AMG Media Networks Limited (AMNL), a unit of Adani Group, declared that it planned to buy RRPR Holding, owner of 29.18% of national news broadcaster NDTV, and made an open offer to buy a further 26%.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] By December 2022, Adani was described as controlling the largest shareholding in NDTV.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2022, Ravi Nair, a freelance journalist was allegedly issued an 'arrest warrant' by the Delhi police without any prior summons after Adani group filed a defamation case against him.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In December 2023, Adani Group acquired majority stake in Indo-Asian News Service.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Independent News Service (INS), the parent company which owns India TV is also backed by Gautam Adani, the chairman of Adani group.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In addition to its industrial interests, the Adani group owns several sports teams, such as the Gujarat Giants team in the Pro Kabaddi League.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2022, Adani Group acquired the Gulf Giants team in UAE's International League T20.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In August 2022, It also purchased a franchise in Legends League Cricket.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In 2023, it purchased a team in the Women's Premier League based in Ahmedabad.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani also sponsored various other sports initiatives, including a 2016 nationwide programme to prepare athletes for Rio Olympics called *Garv Hai* (transl.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] It was re-launched for a second time to groom athletes for 2020 Tokyo Olympics, 2022 Asian Games and Commonwealth Games.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] The programme focuses on archery, shooting, athletics, boxing, and wrestling.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Adani Group has naming rights on Hegvold Stadium (now known as Adani Arena) in Rockhampton and the pavilion end of the Narendra Modi Stadium in Ahmedabad.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] In July 2022, Adani Sportsline was designated as an official partner of the Indian Olympic Association (IOA) for the Birmingham Commonwealth Games 2022, Hangzhou Asian Games 2022, and Paris Olympic Games 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Previously, Adani Sportsline supported the Indian team at the Tokyo Olympics in 2021.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/adani-group] Through its GarvHai initiative, the organisation has supported over 28 athletes, including silver medalist wrestler Ravi Kumar Dahiya.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Although Australia is mostly arid, the nation is a major agricultural producer and exporter, with around 421,000 people employed in agriculture, forestry and fishing as of 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Agriculture's farm gate output was $100 billion per year for a 5.7% share of GDP in 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Farmers and grazers own 135,997 farms, covering 61% of Australia's landmass.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Across the country, there is a mix of irrigation and dry-land farming.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The success of Australian agriculture has been facilitated by long-term policy settings and promotion of reforms that greatly increase investment and, by extension, overall farming output.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] An indicator of the viability of agriculture in the state of South Australia is whether the land is within Goyder's Line.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Aboriginal Australians have been variously described as hunter-gatherer-cultivators and proto-farmers, as there is evidence that farming activities were undertaken prior to the arrival of Europeans, including tilling, planting and irrigating.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] However, these practices were non-industrialised and complementary to hunting, gathering and fishing.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Whether the people could be termed agriculturalists is controversial.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 1788, the first European settlers brought agricultural technology from their homelands which radically changed the dominant practices.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] After some initial failures, wool dominated in the 19th century and, in the first half of the 20th century, dairying increased in its popularity, driven by technological changes like canning and refrigeration.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Meat exports were very significant in the development of Australian agriculture.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] By 1925, there were 54 export freezing works, capable of killing 6000 cattle and 90,000 sheep and lambs daily.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Initially, the meat for British markets had to be frozen, but later beef could be exported chilled.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] At the turn of the millennium, Australia produced a large variety of primary products for export and domestic consumption.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Australia's main crops were contrasting in preferred climate: sugar cane (typical of tropical countries), wheat and barley (typical of cold countries).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Late in 2019, the COVID-19 pandemic began, and Australian agriculture was heavily impacted by the resulting supply chain issues.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The scarcity of freight space and disruption to Chinese New Year purchases was particularly painful, with China being Australia's largest export market and a particularly large buyer of live seafood.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In May, the Australian government proposed an independent investigation of the origin of COVID-19.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Shortly afterwards, China placed large restrictions on their imports of a number of Australian agricultural products, as well as coal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Agriculture is one of Australia's most trade-exposed economic sectors.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The agricultural workforce was heavily reliant on international workers, and by the end of 2020, the pandemic resulted in a severe shortage of farm workers across the country.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Much produce could not be picked, with losses estimated at $22 million, thanks to a backpacker workforce diminished from 200,000 to 52,000.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The shortage lingered through 2021, with skilled labour also in short supply, leading to calls to double Australia's skilled migrant uptake.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Cereals, oilseeds and grain legumes are produced on a large scale in Australia for human consumption and livestock feed.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Wheat is the cereal with the greatest production in terms of area and value to the Australian economy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Sugarcane, grown in tropical Australia, is also an important crop; however, the unsubsidised industry (while lower-cost than heavily subsidised European and American sugar producers) is struggling to compete with the huge and much more efficient Brazilian sugarcane industry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2005, McDonald's Australia Ltd announced it would no longer source all its potatoes for fries from Tasmanian producers and announced a new deal with New Zealand suppliers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Subsequently, Vegetable and Potato Growers Australia (Ltd.) launched a political campaign advocating protectionism.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Olives have been grown in Australia since the early 1800s.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Olive trees were planted by the warden of the self-funded penal settlement on St Helena Island, Queensland in Moreton Bay.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] 3,000 tonnes (3,000 long tons; 3,300 short tons) were used as table olives and around 5–7,000 tonnes (4.9–6,889.4 long tons; 5.5–7,716.2 short tons) exported to the United States, China, the European Union, New Zealand and Japan.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Between 2009 and 2014, Australia imported an average of 31,000 tonnes (31,000 long tons; 34,000 short tons) predominantly from Spain, Italy and Greece.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] China's olive oil consumption is increasing, and Chinese investors have begun to buy Australian olive farms.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Olive cultivars include Arbequina, Arecuzzo, Barnea, Barouni, Coratina, Correggiola, Del Morocco, Frantoio, Hojiblanca, Jumbo Kalamata, Kalamata, Koroneiki, Leccino, Manzanillo, Pendulino, Picholine, Picual, Sevillano, UC13A6, and Verdale.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Manzanillo, Azapa, Nab Tamri and South Australian Verdale produce table olives.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Although the Australian wine industry enjoyed a large period of growth during the 1990s, overplanting and oversupply led to a large drop in the value of wine, forcing out of business some winemakers, especially those on contracts to large wine-producing companies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] A follow-up report from 2019 demonstrated further consolidation, by which stage wine had become Australia's fifth-largest agricultural export industry, with domestic and international sales contributing AU$45.5 billion to gross output.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Wine producers were impacted by the 2019–20 Australian bushfire season, with Adelaide Hills losing 30% of its vineyards.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Grapes around the country were affected by smoke, with the smell affecting the wine produced.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The beef industry is the largest agricultural enterprise in Australia, and it is the second largest beef exporter, behind Brazil, in the world.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] All states and territories of Australia support cattle breeding in a wide range of climates.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Cattle production is a major industry that covers an area in excess of 200 million hectares.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The Australian beef industry is dependent on export markets, with over 60% of Australian beef production exported, primarily to the United States, Korea and Japan.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In southern Australia (NSW, Victoria, Tasmania, South Australia and south-western Western Australia) beef cattle are often reared on smaller properties as part of a mixed farming or grazing operation, but some properties do specialise in producing cattle.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The southern calves are typically reared on pasture and sold as weaners, yearlings or steers at about two years old or older.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Artificial insemination and embryo transfer are more commonly used in stud cattle breeding in Australia, but may be used in other herds.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In the Top End, sub-tropical areas and in arid inland regions, cattle are bred on native pastures on expansive cattle stations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Anna Creek Station in South Australia, Australia is the world's largest working cattle station.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The North Australian Pastoral Company Pty Limited (NAPCO) is now one of Australia's largest beef cattle producers, with a herd of over 180,000 cattle and fourteen cattle stations in Queensland and the Northern Territory.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The Australian Agricultural Company (AA Co) manages a cattle herd of more than 585,000 herd.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Heytesbury Beef Pty Ltd owns and manages over 200,000 herd of cattle across eight stations spanning the East Kimberley, Victoria River and Barkly Tablelands regions in Northern Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Prior to European settlement, there were no cattle in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The present herd consists principally of British and European breeds (Bos taurus) in the southern regions, with Aberdeen Angus and Herefords being the most common.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In northern Australia, Bos indicus breeds predominate along with their crosses.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] They were introduced to combine the resistance to cattle ticks and greater tolerance to hot weather.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 1981, the industry was shaken by the Australian meat substitution scandal, which revealed that horse and kangaroo meat had been both exported overseas and sold domestically as beef.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Domestic milk markets were heavily regulated until the 1980s, particularly for milk used for domestic fresh milk sales.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] This protected smaller producers in the northern states who produced exclusively for their local markets.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The Kerin Plan (named after politician John Kerin) began the process of deregulation in 1986.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The final price supports were removed in 2000 with the assistance of Pat Rowley, head of the Australian Dairy Farmers Federation and the Australian Dairy Industry Council.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Deregulation ultimately saw 13,000 Australian dairy farmers produce 10 billion litres of milk in comparison to the 5 billion litres of milk produced by 23,000 farmers prior to deregulation, a 30% reduction in farmers with a 55% rise in milk production.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] As the Australian dairy industry grows, feedlot systems are becoming more popular.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Australia is the world's largest producer of wool.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The Australian wool industry was worth $3.6 billion in 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The total number of sheep is estimated to be 75 million.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In the late 1980s, the sheep flock was 180 million.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Only 5% of Australia's wool clip is processed onshore.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The Merino produces fine wool and was first introduced to Australia in 1797, with the breed being well-suited to the Australian environment.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] By the 1870s Australia had become the world's greatest wool-growing nation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The fisheries in Australia is a very large scale industry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Australia produces many species of fish, including farmed, sustainable and intensive, and wild caught such as tuna and other schooling fish.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The shorelines, especially the Great Barrier Reef, are providing motivation to help the continent by using seaweed (algae) to absorb nutrients.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Because of the giant number of natural Australian seaweeds, not only could seaweed cultivation be used to help absorb nutrients around the GBR and other Australian shores, cultivation could also help feed a large part of the world.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Even the Chinese, who could be considered far more advanced in seaweed cultivation, are interested in the future of Australian seaweeds.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Lastly, the GBR itself, because of the delicate corals, has lent itself to utilising seaweed/algae purposely as a nutrient reduction tool in the form of algae.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Australian farmers and their spokesman have always considered that life on the land is inherently more virtuous, more healthy, more important and more productive than living in the towns and cities.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The farmers complained that something was wrong with an electoral system which produced parliamentarians who spent money beautifying vampire-cities instead of developing the interior.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The Country Party, from the 1920s to the 1970s, promulgated its version of agrarianism, which it called "countrymindedness".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The goal was to enhance the status of the graziers (operators of sheep properties) and small farmers and justified subsidies for them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Water management is a major issue in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The nation is struggling with over-allocation issues and increasing variability.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Effectively governing such issues has proven to be problematic.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Public institutions responsible for water management include the Murray–Darling Basin Authority, which manages water resources in the Murray–Darling basin, Australia's largest river catchment.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Because of Australia's large deserts and irregular rainfall, irrigation is necessary for agriculture in some parts of the country.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The total gross value of irrigated agricultural production in 2004-05 was A$9,076 million compared to A$9,618 million in 2000–01.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The gross value of irrigated agricultural production represents around a quarter (23%) of the gross value of agricultural commodities produced in Australia in 2004–05, on less than 1% of agricultural land.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2006, the CSIRO, the federal government agency for scientific research in Australia, forecast that climate change will cause decreased precipitation over much of Australia and that this will exacerbate existing challenges to water availability and quality for agriculture.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Climate change has damaged farming productivity, reducing broadacre farm profits by an average of 22% since 2000.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2023, the Department of Agriculture published a National Statement on Climate Change and Agriculture, exploring resilience in the agriculture sector.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Agriculture contributes 13% of Australia's total greenhouse emissions, however, much of this is methane of biological origin, rather than from fossil fuels.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Although native, kangaroos have been known to destroy fences and eat cattle feed, sometimes in problematic numbers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] As of 2021, $2.3 billion worth of commodities were produced in Australia by the organic agriculture sector, representing approximately 3% of agricultural output.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Australia leads the world with 35 million hectares certified organic, which is 8.8% of Australia's agricultural land and Australia now accounts for more than half (51%) of the world's certified organic agriculture hectares.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] GM grains are widely grown in all states and territories in Australia with the exception of Tasmania, which is the last state to maintain a moratorium against GM.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] GM crops are regulated under a national scheme by the Gene Technology Regulator, through the Gene Technology Act 2000.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] As of 2022, there are four GM crops approved to be grown in Australia: cotton, safflower, carnations and canola.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In particular, 99.5% of cotton growers in Australia use GM cotton.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Australia has seen a major increase in foreign ownership of agriculture in the 2010s.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] According to a report in 2020, it was found that the amount of Australian agricultural land in foreign ownership, increased slightly from 13.4 to 13.8 percent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] A 2016 Lowy Institute poll found that 87% of respondents were against the Federal Government allowing foreign companies to buy Australian agricultural land a 6% points higher than a similar survey four years ago.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] A 2022 ABC's Vote Compass Poll found that 88% of Australians want tighter controls on foreign ownership of farm land, which is an increase from Compass poll results in 2013 and 2016.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Animal welfare has caused public concern, with exports of live animals particularly scrutinised.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The practice of exporting live animals has received strong public opposition (a petition carrying 200,000 signatures of people opposed to live export was tabled in parliament) and opposition from the RSPCA because of cruelty.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2022, the Labor Party committed to ending live exports of sheep, if elected.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2023, they commenced the process, however, it is not likely to be completed within the government's first term.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2006, animal rights organisations including PETA promoted a boycott of Merino wool, as a protest against the practice of mulesing, a procedure used to prevent the animals from becoming fly blown with maggots.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2004, due to the worldwide attention, AWI proposed to phase out the practice by the end of year 2010; this promise was retracted in 2009.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] In 2022, new regulations for chicken welfare were introduced.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Farming is the most dangerous occupation in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Accidents involving tractors accounted for 20 per cent and quad bikes for 14 per cent of deaths.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Drone technology, self driver tractors, and online marketplaces are recent and growing trends.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] There is little standardisation and no accreditation authorities, though the CSIRO and other independent organisations have evaluated individual developments, the lack of a coordinated approach and lead agency restricts developments and risks Australia's competitiveness.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] Before the Federation of Australia in 1901, individual state governments bore responsibility for agriculture.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] As part of the federation, the Department of Commerce and Agriculture was created to help develop the agricultural industry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] The newly created Department of Trade and Customs had additional responsibilities for sugar agreements, as well as cotton.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/agriculture-in-australia] These responsibilities were merged into a single agricultural department in 1956.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The **Albanese government** is the sitting federal government of Australia, led by Prime Minister Anthony Albanese of the Labor Party.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The Albanese government was sworn in on 23 May 2022 by the governor-general of Australia, David Hurley.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The party governed with a two-to-three seat majority in the House of Representatives in its first term, and expanded its majority to 19 seats in its second term.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] It won a plurality of seats in the Senate at the 2025 election, though has never held a majority of seats in the upper house.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Albanese succeeded the Morrison government after the Liberal–National Coalition was defeated at the 2022 election, and saw the first Labor government to be elected at the federal level since the Rudd government was defeated at the 2013 election.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The Albanese government went on win a landslide victory in the 2025 federal election, making Albanese the first Prime Minister to serve a full term and win another since John Howard's victory at the 2004 election.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The 2022 election was called by Morrison on 10 April 2022, when he visited the Governor-General advising the latter to prorogue Parliament and dissolve the House of Representatives.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The Governor-General accepted Morrison's recommendations, as is the custom in Australia's Westminster system of government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The Parliament was then prorogued and the House of Representatives dissolved the next morning.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] As of 10:00PM AEST on election night, the Labor Party (led by Anthony Albanese) was projected to form a government by ABC News, although it was not clear whether they would have a majority or a minority.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] After the bulk of the votes had been counted and a Labor victory appeared inevitable, Morrison conceded the election, and then announced his intention to resign as the Liberal Party leader.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The Coalition's loss was attributed to Morrison's unpopularity with voters and the popularity of centrist "teal independents" in certain inner-city electorates.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Albanese, who also made history as the first Italian-Australian to secure the position of Prime Minister, was sworn in as the new Prime Minister of Australia on 23 May 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On 9 February 2023, former Liberal Party cabinet minister Alan Tudge resigned from Parliament, triggering a by-election in his seat of Aston.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] In an unexpected result, Labor's Mary Doyle won the by-election, marking the first time a governing party won a by-election against the opposition since 1920.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] As a result of this, Albanese's government increased their majority in the House of Representatives to 78 of 151 seats.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Although it was not certain on election night that Labor would win a majority, no other party could realistically form a government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Accordingly, two days after the election, Albanese, deputy leader Richard Marles, shadow treasurer Jim Chalmers, and senators Penny Wong and Katy Gallagher were sworn in as an interim five-person ministry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The five ministers divided all portfolios between them until the full ministry was determined.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] According to Australia's ABC News, the governor-general David Hurley would not have sworn in Albanese without assurances that Labor could provide stable government, as well as legal advice that this was the proper course of action.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Albanese confirmed that he secured confidence and supply from the crossbench in the event that he was not able to form majority government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Albanese announced the composition of his full first ministry on 31 May 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Given that frontbenchers Kristina Keneally and Terri Butler were not re-elected, Murray Watt and Clare O’Neil were chosen by the Labor caucus to replace them in the cabinet.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] With 19 female frontbenchers and 10 female cabinet ministers, it became the most gender-equal ministry in Australian history.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] The full ministry was sworn in by Governor-General David Hurley on 1 June 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Albanese announced a reshuffle of his Ministry on 28 July 2024 due to the impending retirements of Linda Burney and Brendan O'Connor.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Senator Malarndirri McCarthy succeeded Burney as the Minister for Indigenous affairs while Andrew Giles assumed the Skills and Training portfolio.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Clare O'Neil also assumed the housing portfolio.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Following the 2025 Australian federal election held on 3 May 2025, a cabinet reshuffle occurred in mid-May.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Phil Gaetjens, the Secretary of the Department of Prime Minister and Cabinet under Scott Morrison, took leave the day before the Albanese government was sworn in.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] This had been expected given Albanese had indicated he would not want Gaetjens to continue in the role.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On 6 June 2022, former University of Melbourne vice-chancellor Glyn Davis replaced Gaetjens.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] In June 2024, the government announced that Matt Kean, a former Liberal Treasurer of New South Wales, would be appointed to lead the Climate Change Authority.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On 17 October 2022, the government appointed Jayne Jagot as a Justice of the High Court of Australia, replacing the retiring Justice Patrick Keane.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On Jagot's appointment, the High Court of Australia had a majority of female Justices for the first time in its history.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On 6 November 2023, the government appointed Robert Beech-Jones as a High Court Justice.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Beech-Jones replaced Stephen Gageler, who was made the Chief Justice of Australia upon the retirement of Susan Kiefel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] These appointments ended the brief female majority on the court.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On 30 September 2022, the government announced that it had nominated former Defence Minister Stephen Smith as the next High Commissioner of Australia to the United Kingdom.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Smith commenced his position in January 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On 20 December 2022, the government announced that it had nominated former Prime Minister Kevin Rudd as the next Ambassador of Australia to the United States.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Rudd commenced his position in March 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] On 3 April 2024, the Prime Minister announced that King Charles III had approved Albanese's appointment of Sam Mostyn to succeed General David Hurley as Governor-General of Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Mostyn commenced her position on 1 July 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] In July 2024, owing to the rise in antisemitic activity in Australia following the October 7 attacks in Israel, Albanese appointed Jillian Segal as Australian special envoy on combatting antisemitism.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Segal has a long history of advocacy for Jewish communities and combating antisemitism, and her appointment was supported by the federal opposition.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] In October 2024, Albanese appointed Malik as Australian special envoy on combatting Islamophobia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p01] Malik is a prominent Muslim leader and advocate for interfaith dialogue.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Jim Chalmers was sworn in as Treasurer of Australia and Katy Gallagher was sworn in as Finance Minister as part of the interim Albanese ministry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Albanese government commenced amidst the 2021–23 global surge in inflation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Australian inflation rate peaked at 7.5% at the end of 2022, a 32-year high, before easing to 2.8% by October 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Between 4 May 2022 and 8 November 2023, the Reserve Bank of Australia steadily raised interest rates from 0.10% to 4.35%, a 12-year high.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Bank then maintained the rate of 4.35% until cutting it to 4.10% on 19 February 2025, the first rate cut since March 2020.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 28 February 2023, the government announced that it would seek to reduce tax concessions on superannuation accounts with more than $3 million.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In November 2023 it introduced legislation to do this, but was unable to secure support for it from the Senate.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In January 2024, the Albanese government announced a restructuring of the "Stage Three" tax cuts that had been passed by the previous government but had not yet come into effect.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Albanese government's restructuring gave greater tax benefits to those earning under $150,000 whilst reducing the original tax cut for higher earners.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Coalition criticised Albanese for breaking a promise not to change the cuts and initially suggested they would not support it, but did eventually support the legislation's passage in February 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The modified tax cuts came into effect on 1 July 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 27 March 2025, as part of its fourth budget, the Albanese government legislated a further tax cut that Chalmers called "modest but meaningful".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This tax cut will reduce the 16% rate for the lowest tax bracket ($18,201 and $45,000) for all taxpayers, down to 15% on 1 July 2026 and then to 14% on 1 July 2027.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Early in the government's term, Treasurer Chalmers confirmed that the new government would hand down a revised budget in October 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In the lead up to the October budget, Chalmers and Gallagher launched an audit to highlight any waste left behind by the previous government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Secretary of the Department of Treasury Steven Kennedy noted that the budget needed to be brought under control and that the tax system needed to be made fit for use.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 25 October 2022, Chalmers handed down a revised budget — the first under the Albanese government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The budget forecast that inflation would peak at 7.75% at the end of the year.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The budget also took steps to fund the government's election promises largely by using funding earmarked by the former government which had not yet been spent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In May 2023, Chalmers handed down the government's second budget.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The budget delivered a surplus of $22.1 billion (equivalent to 0.9% of Australia's GDP), which was well above the government's forecasted surplus of $4.3 billion; this was Australia's first budget surplus in 15 years, and the largest ever Australian budget surplus.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In May 2024, Chalmers handed down the government's third budget.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This budget delivered a surplus of $9.3 billion, making it the first consecutive surplus in an Australian federal budget since 2007–08.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In May 2025, Chalmers handed down the government's fourth budget.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In April 2024, Prime Minister Albanese announced a major industrial policy called "Future Made in Australia", which seeks to promote Australian manufacturing in sustainable energy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] As part of the policy, the government's third budget contained $22.7 billion over a decade in support of domestic green hydrogen, solar-panel manufacturing, and mining of critical minerals.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This includes a $1 billion "Solar Sunshot" program to support solar panel manufacturing in Australia, and a $566 million "Resourcing Australia's Prosperity" initiative for geomapping for mining resources.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In July 2024, the Albanese government introduced legislation to give further effect to the policy, which passed the Parliament in November 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] As part of the Parliamentary negotiations, $500 million for the electrification of social housing was added to the scheme.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Tony Burke served as Minister for Employment from 2022 to 2024, succeeded by Senator Murray Watt after a July 2024 reshuffle of Cabinet.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 3 June 2022, Minister Burke confirmed that the government had made a formal submission to the Fair Work Commission in support of an increase to the minimum wage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Subsequently, on 15 June 2022, the Fair Work Commission announced that the minimum wage would be raised by 5.2%.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In September 2022, in fulfilment of a campaign promise, Albanese held a "Jobs and Skills Summit" with unions and business leaders.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] It resulted in the government agreeing to 36 initiatives involving education, housing, workplace relations, and immigration.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 28 November 2022, the government passed new workplace harassment laws through the Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] These laws implement the recommendation of the Respect@Work Report to create a positive duty requiring employers to implement measures to prevent sexual harassment, sex discrimination, and victimisation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 2 December 2022, the government passed its *Secure Jobs, Better Pay* law through the Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The new law allows unions to negotiate multi-employer pay deals in an effort to secure wage increases across particular sectors such as child care and aged care.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The law also aims to close the gender pay gap by prohibiting pay secrecy employment clauses and secures the right of workers to seek flexible working arrangements.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Despite opposition from the Liberal Party and business lobbies, the first part of the bill was passed by the Senate on 7 December 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The second tranche of legislation, which introduced minimum standards for gig workers, was passed on 8 February 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 13 December 2023, Australian federal and state workplace ministers agreed to ban the use, supply, and manufacturing of engineered stone from 1 July 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This initiative followed a Safe Work Australia report that found the rates of silicosis and silica-related diseases had risen substantially particularly among engineered stone workers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In mid-January 2024, Burke declined to intervene in an industrial dispute between the Australian Maritime Officers Union and DP World but criticised the latter for allegedly acting in "bad faith".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In its May 2024 budget, the government announced that superannuation would be added to Commonwealth-funded paid parental leave from 1 July 2025.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In late August 2024, the federal government's right to disconnect laws came into effect.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This allows employees to ignore calls or messages from their employers outside of work hours, except where such refusal is unreasonable.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Clare O'Neil was appointed Minister for Home Affairs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Prior to her appointment, on 27 May 2022, interim Minister Jim Chalmers announced that he had exercised his power to allow the Murugappan family to return home to Biloela on bridging visas.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In September 2022, the Albanese government increased the permanent migration intake from 160,000 to a record 195,000 a year.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Net overseas migration reached 536,000 in the 2022–23 financial year, the highest in Australian history, which the Albanese government attributed to being a "catch-up" on the migration decrease during the COVID-19 border closures in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Net overseas migration then decreased to 446,000 in the 2023–24 financial year, and is estimated to be 340,000 over the 2024–25 financial year.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Net permanent and long-term arrivals in the 12 months to May 2025 were 447,620.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In October 2022, the Albanese government repatriated four Australian-citizen ISIS brides and their 13 children from Syria to western Sydney, which some local mayors and representative Dai Le criticised.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] As of June 2024, the government has not repatriated any further ISIS brides or their children.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In the leadup to the 2022 election, Labor promised that it would abolish temporary protection visas.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] It did so by early 2023, allowing 19,000 asylum seekers who had been living in Australia for a decade to gain permanent residency.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In November 2023, the High Court held that indefinite immigration detention is unlawful.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response to this ruling and demands from those indefinitely detained, the Albanese government began releasing people clearly impacted by the case.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Within a week, 80 people were released, with Giles saying that all are on visa conditions including reporting.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Albanese government is seeking to clarify if the government must release people from immigration detention if they have refused to cooperate with attempts to deport them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The government is seeking to enact legislation that will jail immigration detainees and unlawful non-citizens for a minimum of one year if they do not cooperate with attempts to deport them.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In December 2023, the Albanese government released its ten-year migration strategy which includes increasing minimum English language requirements for international students and tightening visa processes for migrant workers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] According to some critics, the housing crisis in Australia was exacerbated by the immigration policies of the Albanese government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In January 2024, the government signalled changes that would make it easier for international students to settle permanently in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] However, on 1 July 2024, the government enacted policy changes intended to limit the available of visas for international student graduates.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 1 July 2024, the government announced plans to increase the fee for international student visas from $710 to $1600.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Representatives from the university sector expressed concern that the increased fee would deter international students from studying in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 27 August 2024, the Australian Government announced plans to limit the number of international student tertiary enrolments to 270,000, with 145,000 enrolments allocated to university enrolments.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 6 September 2024, the government announced the maximum number of student enrolments allocated to each Australian university.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response to the Albanese Government's announcement, the Allen government in Victoria voiced concerns that the change could cost the Victorian economy $5.9 billion by 2027.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] During a senate inquiry into the proposed legislation, representatives from the Australian university sector voiced similar concerns about the economic impact of the policy, and the consequent effects on long term tertiary education outcomes for both international and domestic students.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Mark Butler was appointed Health Minister.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] During the 2022 election campaign, Labor committed $135 million to fund 50 bulk-billed urgent care clinics, a policy designed to ease pressure on hospital emergency wards.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] By the start of 2024, 58 clinics had opened across every state and territory of Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Over the first six months of operation, more than 130,000 patients were treated for non-life-threatening medical emergencies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In October 2022, the government's cheaper medications bill passed the parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The new law reduced the cost of PBS medications by 29% and reduced the co-payment.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The first bill to pass the new Parliament was one responding to the 17 recommendations of the Aged Care Royal Commission.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The legislation amended the aged care funding model and introduces new reporting and transparency requirements.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The government also introduced a bill in the first sitting of the new parliament seeking to implement its election commitment to ensure that there is a nurse in nursing homes at all times.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This bill was passed by the Parliament on 27 October 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The government entered submissions to the Fair Work Commission supporting the case for a wage increase in the aged care industry and committed to funding any such increase.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Commission ordered a 15% increase and the government is expected to enter submissions related to the timing and implementation of this.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In mid-August 2022, the federal government announced that providers in the National Disability Insurance Scheme would be scrutinised for fraud.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The government also confirmed the establishment of a multiagency task force to look into this issue.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 7 July 2024, the NDIS Minister Bill Shorten confirmed that sex work would no longer be funded through the NDIS under planned reforms.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 5 September 2024, Shorten confirmed that he would retire from politics and his ministerial portfolio in February 2025 in order to take up the position as vice-chancellor of the University of Canberra.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 10 November 2024, health minister Mark Butler announced that pregnant women and newborn babies would have access to free respiratory syncytial virus vaccines before winter 2025 under the National Immunisation Program.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In addition, babies would be eligible for national access to monoclonal antibody.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 22 February 2025, Albanese announced that the government would invest $8.5 billion in Medicare services including $18 million in subsidised general practitioner's visits, 400 nursing scholarships and general practitioner training programs for 2,000 doctors.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 30 June 2022, Butler ordered an inquiry into Australia's COVID-19 vaccine supplies, future variant jabs and how the rollout was caught short at the height of the pandemic.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The review will also examine the deals entered into by the former Morrison government to purchase vaccines and therapeutic treatments.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Pandemic leave payments and access to free rapid antigen tests for concession card holders expired on 1 July 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The new government initially did not take steps to extend these programs, but reinstated them on 16 July 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 3 July 2022, Butler announced that from 12:01 am on 6 July 2022 changes to the Biosecurity Act would come into effect which provide that persons seeking to visit Australia would no longer have to declare their COVID-19 vaccination status.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 7 July 2022, Butler confirmed that persons aged over 30 would be eligible to receive a fourth COVID-19 vaccine dose from 11 July 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The government altered rules governing isolation periods so that persons infected with the virus only need isolate for 5 days from 9 September 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Albanese announced on 30 September that a mandatory isolation period would no longer apply at all for persons infected with COVID-19.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 21 September 2023, Albanese announced an independent inquiry into the federal government's handling of the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia, led by former public servant Robyn Kruk, infectious diseases expert Catherine Bennett and economist Angela Jackson.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The royal inquiry drew criticism from the Australian Medical Association and the Human Rights Commissioner for excluding state and territorial governments from its scope.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Chris Bowen was appointed Minister for Climate Change and Energy in the Albanese ministry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 16 June 2022, Bowen and Albanese submitted a new Nationally Determined Contribution to the United Nations which formally committed Australia to reducing carbon emissions by 43% on 2005 levels.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This represented an increase from the 26–28% reduction target submitted by the Abbott government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Albanese government also codified the new reduction target in legislation, which passed with support from the Greens and crossbench senators.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In late 2022, the Albanese government announced reforms to the "safeguard mechanism", which requires Australia's largest carbon emitters to keep their emissions under a "baseline limit", either by reducing emissions or purchasing carbon credits.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The scheme was introduced by the Turnbull government in 2016, but failed to reduce emissions as the rules were often left unenforced.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] However, the Albanese amendments were met by opposition from the Australian Greens, whose support was crucial in the Senate; Greens leader Adam Bandt argued that the reforms did not go far enough.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The two parties reached an agreement on 27 March 2023, with the Greens negotiating a "hard cap" on emissions that cannot be offset by carbon credits.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The bill was passed on 30 March 2023, marking the most significant piece of climate change legislation passed through the Australian Parliament since 2011's *Clean Energy Act*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In late 2023, Australia re-joined the United Nations' Green Climate Fund, from which the previous Morrison government had withdrawn in 2018.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] As part of re-joining, the Albanese government committed $150 million in climate finance to Pacific island countries.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In late March 2024, Albanese along with Bowen and industry minister Ed Husic travelled to the former Liddell Power Station in the Hunter Valley to announce a $1 billion solar panel program.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The visit later attracted criticism and accusations of hypocrisy after it was revealed that the ministers had travelled into the area on two separate private jets.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response to criticism, Bowen said that the Royal Australian Air Force had been responsible for their travel arrangements.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In April 2022, shortly before the Albanese government took office, the independent Australian Energy Regulator (AER) determined that the retail electricity pricing cap would be lifted on 1 July 2022 in response to higher wholesale prices.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Amidst the global surge in energy prices, Australia entered into an energy crisis marked by significantly increased power prices.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Bowen convened a meeting with his state and territory counterparts on 8 June 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The ministers agreed to expedite work on a capacity mechanism which will require the AER to pay retailers to maintain excess capacity.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 9 December 2022, Albanese announced that National Cabinet had agreed to a co-ordinated plan to introduce temporary caps on gas and coal prices.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Bill passed the federal Parliament on 15 December 2022, creating a 12-month cap on energy prices and a $1.5 billion relief package for households and businesses.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In May 2024, as part of the Albanese government's third budget, every Australian household received a $300 credit on their energy bill via four quarterly instalments of $75.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In May 2025, as part of its fourth budget, the government added a further $150 credit by extending the instalments by another two quarters.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In July 2022, the Albanese government introduced a bill to exempt certain electric vehicles from fringe benefits tax.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This passed Parliament in November 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In March 2024, the Albanese government introduced a bill to apply a vehicle emission standard to new vehicles sold in Australia from 1 July 2025.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Parliament passed this New Vehicle Efficiency Standard in May 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Albanese said that electric vehicles "can do anything that petrol vehicles can do, they'll do it in a way which is more efficient, that boosts productivity, that saves money, as well as driving down emissions".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Tanya Plibersek was appointed Minister for the Environment and Water.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Plibersek attended the UN ocean conference in Lisbon on 26 June 2022 where she announced five new blue carbon projects which are understood to include assistance for developing nations to safeguard the health of their oceans.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 19 July 2022, Plibersek released the State of the Environment Report which had been handed to the previous government in December 2021.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Report provided that every category of the Australian environment – apart from urban environments – was now in a poor and deteriorating state.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response, Plibersek announced that the government would adopt a new target of protecting 30% of the Australian environment and promised stronger environmental protection legislation to be introduced in 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 8 December 2022, Plibersek announced that the government would commit to a reform of federal environmental laws, in response to an independent review first submitted to the Morrison government in 2020.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The government planned to introduce legislation to Parliament before the end of 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 29 May 2024, Plibersek introduced to Parliament a modified version of the reforms.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In mid-May 2024, the Federal Court of Australia ruled Plibersek in her capacity as federal environment minister did not need to consider the environmental impacts of emissions when approving gas or coal projects.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 5 June 2023, Plibersek announced that the government would triple the size of the Macquarie Island Marine Park, with the vast majority of the park being completely closed to fishing, mining, and other extractive activities.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This expansion came into effect on 1 July 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 8 October 2024, Plibersek announced that the government would quadruple the size of the Heard and McDonald Islands Marine Park, representing an increase of 310,000 square kilometres in protected area of restricted fishing.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This expansion came into effect on 24 January 2025 and means that over half of Australia's ocean area is under protection.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] At Albanese's first press conference as Prime Minister, the podium flags in the blue room at Parliament were changed to include Indigenous and Torres Strait Islander flags in addition to the Australian flag.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Upon the opening of the new Parliament, both flags began to be displayed in the House of Representatives and Senate chambers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Linda Burney was sworn in as Minister for Indigenous Australians on 1 June 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] She was the first Indigenous woman to serve in the role.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In July 2024, following Minister Burney's retirement from the Cabinet, her Assistant Minister Malarndirri McCarthy became the new Minister for Indigenous Australians.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Disparity in health and socio-economic outcomes between First Nations peoples and non-Indigenous, remained an issue under the Albanese Government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In February 2024, data released by the Australian Productivity Commission indicating that only five of 19 target health and socioeconomic outcomes were on track to reach parity by the intended 2031 deadline.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] When declaring victory on election night, Albanese confirmed that his government was committed to implementing the Uluru Statement from the Heart in full within its first term.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 3 February 2023, all first ministers signed a statement of intent through the National Cabinet committing to support constitutional recognition of a Voice to Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] A referendum on an Indigenous Voice to Parliament was held on the 14 October 2023 and was rejected nationally.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Yes23 campaign co-chair Rachel Perkins called for a week of silence "to grieve this outcome and reflect on its meaning and significance".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 3 August 2024, Albanese announced his government no longer intended to pursue Truth and Treaty through the establishment of a formal Makaratta Commission.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In May 2024, the federal government allocated $6.5 million from the 2024 Australian federal budget to a pilot age verification scheme meant to protect children from accessing pornography and other harmful digital content in response to a sharp rise in domestic violence nationally.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 10 September 2024, Albanese and Minister for Communications Michelle Rowland confirmed that the federal government would introduce legislation to enforce a minimum age for access to social media and other relevant digital platforms.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Albanese said that the legislation was intended to safeguard the safety and mental and physical health of young people, while Rowland said that the proposed legislation would hold big tech to account for harmful online environments and social media addiction among children.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The federal government's announcement followed South Australia's plan to restrict social media access to people aged 14 and above, and the Coalition's promise to restrict social media access to people aged under 16 if it won the 2025 Australian federal election.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response, the Australian Association of Psychologists director Carly Dober described the proposal as a "bandaid response to a very complicated and deeply entrenched issue".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Australian Internet regulator, the eSafety Commissioner, who expressed concern that a social media ban would exclude young people from "meaningful" digital engagement and access to critical support.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] By contrast, the 36Months initiative has supported the social media age limit on the grounds that excessive social media usage was "rewiring young brains" and causing an "epidemic of mental illness".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 7 November 2024, Albanese confirmed that the minimum age would be 16 and would not include exemptions for young people who already have social media accounts or those with parental consent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 21 November, the Albanese government introduced the legislation with proposed fines of up to A$49.5 million (US$32 million) on social media platforms for systemic breaches.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The proposed law would affect Facebook, Instagram, TikTok, X (formerly Twitter) and Snapchat.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] However, Albanese confirmed that children would still have access to messaging, online gaming, and health and education-related services including the youth mental health platform Headspace, Google Classroom and YouTube, Messenger Kids, WhatsApp and Kids Helpline.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 29 November 2024, the Australian Parliament passed the legislation with support from the Coalition but opposition from the Australian Greens.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response, tech companies Meta Platforms, TikTok and Google criticised the age verification legislation but indicated they would work with the government to implement the legislation over the next 12 months.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 26 November 2025, the Digital Freedom Project announced it would commence legal action in the High Court against the new laws, saying they violate the implied right to political communication in the Constitution.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Following the 2024 Wakeley church stabbing on 15 April 2024, the federal government ordered Meta Platforms and X (formerly Twitter) to remove offensive content relating to the attack within 24 hours or face fines.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response, X announced it would challenge the federal government's decision in court, with its owner Elon Musk accusing the government of censorship.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Federal Court of Australia said that it was unreasonable for the eSafety Commission to require X to remove access to the video globally and noted that a block would be ignored by other countries.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The eSafety Commissioner Julie Inman Grant dropped the Federal Court case on 5 June 2024, but stated that she would continue legal action in the Administrative Appeals Tribunal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 12 September 2024, the federal government introduced legislation to combat social media misinformation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] It would allow the Australian Communications and Media Authority (ACMA) to require social media platforms to set internal industry standards around serious harm to election integrity, public health, incitement of hatred and violence, and disruption of key infrastructure or emergency services.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The ACMA would have the power to fine social media companies up to five percent of their annual revenue for non-compliance.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In response, X's owner Musk denounced the Australian government as "fascists".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 4 April 2023, the Albanese government banned the video streaming app TikTok on all government devices, including the mobile phones of politicians.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Prior to the Australian federal government's ban, 68 federal agencies had banned TikTok on work-related mobile devices by early March 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The federal government subsequently began a review of TikTok on 21 March 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In June 2024, the Albanese government introduced legislation to criminalise the creation and sharing of non-consensual deepfake pornography.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The legislation passed the Parliament two months later with broad political support.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In November 2024, the Albanese government passed legislation that criminalised doxxing.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Jason Clare was appointed Minister for Education.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] On 17 June 2022, Clare confirmed that the Albanese government intends to make changes which give schools a choice of whether to hire a religious or secular pastoral care worker through the National School Chaplaincy Programme.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Clare announced an Australian Universities Accord with the terms of reference covering funding, affordability, employment conditions for staff, and how universities and TAFEs can work together.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The Accord's final report is due to be handed down in December 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In November 2024, the Albanese government passed legislation to change the calculation of annual indexation on student university debts.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Previously it was based on the consumer price index (CPI), with the change making it determined by what is lower between the CPI or the wage price index (wage growth).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The change in indexation removed an estimated $3 billion in Australian student debt loans.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The 10-year anniversary of the Gonski report in May 2022 led to criticism of successive state governments failure to implement its recommendations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] By the late March 2025 all states and territories had signed on to the new school funding agreement with the Albanese government lifting federal funding of public schools to 25 per cent from 20 per cent, under the Better and Fairer Schools Agreement (BFSA).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] Under the BFSA, states are required to increase their funding of public schools to 75 per cent of the minimum amount recommended by the 2012 Gonski Report and Gonski 2.0, per the Schooling Resource Standard proposed by panel chair David Gonski.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] This means that they will be fully funded according to the Gonski model.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] In November 2022, the parliament passed the government's cheaper childcare laws.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p02] The new laws commenced operation in July 2023 and increased the childcare subsidy from 85% to 90% for families on an income below $80,000.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Julie Collins was appointed Minister for Housing, in the midst of a housing affordability crisis.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 1 October 2022, the government launched its Regional First Home Buyer Guarantee.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The program provides a government guarantee of up to 15 per cent for eligible first home buyers, so regional Australians with a deposit of as little as 5 per cent can avoid paying lenders’ mortgage insurance.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In August 2023, Albanese reached an agreement with National Cabinet to build 1.2 million houses over five years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 13 September 2023, the government's Housing Australia Future Fund passed the Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This is a $10 billion investment fund controlled by the Future Fund that is designed to build 30,000 new social and affordable homes over the following five years in a further effort to increase supply.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 25 September 2024, the Albanese government instructed the Treasury to examine negative gearing.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] As a divisive wedge issue in Australian politics, changes to negative gearing rules were proposed by Labor prior to the 2019 election, in which they were defeated.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese had previously pledged not to modify negative gearing as Opposition Leader, leading to criticism from the Coalition and conservative media outlets for appearing to backtrack on this promise.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] After intense media speculation, Albanese ruled out making changes to negative gearing the next day.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The Albanese government announced that existing mutual obligation penalties would be expunged from people's records as the government transitioned to the Workforce Australia system for JobSeeker, saying that it was "too late" to scrap the system.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] A review of the Workforce Australia JobSeeker scheme will be tabled in parliament in September 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Legislation to end the Cashless Debit Card was passed by the House of Representatives, and will be considered by the Senate in September.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Cashless Debit Card users in the Northern Territory will be transitioned back onto the BasicsCard, a Howard-era income management scheme, despite Labor promising prior to the election to end compulsory income management.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] A Royal Commission into the Robodebt Scheme was announced by Albanese with Letters Patent issued on 25 August 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The Royal Commission will be chaired by former Queensland Supreme Court Justice Catherine Holmes and is expected to conclude on 18 April 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The Albanese government agreed to all recommendations of the royal commission, either in full or in principle, but rejected a recommendation about the freedom of information act.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] During the election campaign, Albanese confirmed that his government would seek to establish a federal National Anti-Corruption Commission within its first year in office.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On the day he was sworn in, Albanese confirmed that he had already ordered work to begin on this task.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Attorney-General Mark Dreyfus said that the government's legislation would include provision for the commission to investigate pork-barrelling, as well as "serious and systemic" past corruption allegations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In September 2022, Dreyfus introduced a bill to establish a National Anti-Corruption Commission (NACC).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The bill passed the Parliament on 30 November 2022 in line with the government's commitment to establish an anti-corruption commission prior to the end of 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The NACC came into existence on 1 July 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 16 December 2022, the Labor Albanese government announced that it will abolish the Administrative Appeals Tribunal (AAT) and replace it with a new body, claiming that the AAT had been "fatally compromised" by political appointments and "cronyism".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 28 May 2024, the legislation to establish the AAT's replacement, the Administrative Review Tribunal (ART), passed the Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The new Tribunal commenced in October 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In June 2023, the Albanese government introduced legislation to ban the public display of terrorist or Nazi symbols, including the Nazi salute.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The ban passed Parliament in December 2023 and came into effect the following month.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 7 July 2022, Attorney-General Mark Dreyfus exercised his power under section 71 of the *Judiciary Act* to cease proceedings against Bernard Collaery in connection with the Australia–East Timor spying scandal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In 2022, the incoming Albanese government indicated that it opposed the continued prosecution of Julian Assange but intended to pursue quiet diplomacy to prevent it.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 14 August 2023, US ambassador to Australia Caroline Kennedy flagged a potential plea deal for Assange, shortly after meeting with a group of Australian parliamentarians pushing for Assange's return.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 24 June 2024, Assange agreed to a plea bargain with the US Department, in which Assange would plead guilty to one felony count of violating the Espionage Act in exchange for immediate release.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The agreement entailed the US Department of Justice seeking a sentence of 62 months, the time he had served in British prison while awaiting extradition.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] After release from British prison, Assange immediately flew via charter flight – with the accompaniment of his legal representatives and the Australian High Commissioner to the United Kingdom, Stephen Smith – to Saipan to the District Court for the Northern Mariana Islands.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] After arrival, Assange and Smith were joined by the Australian Ambassador to the United States, Kevin Rudd.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Judge Ramona Villagomez Manglona accepted Assange's guilty plea and sentenced him to 62 months' time served.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Assange then returned to the charter flight and flew to Canberra.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Assange was required by the Australian government to repay the costs of the charter flight, requested at US$520,000, as he was not permitted to fly on commercial airlines.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Upon arrival in Australia, Albanese phoned Assange.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Assange's lawyer later recounted that Assange had said that Albanese had "saved his life" and that Rudd and Smith were the "diplomatic A-team".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Murray Watt was sworn in as Minister for Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry in late May 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Following a cabinet reshuffle in July 2024, he was succeeded by Julie Collins.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 11 May 2024, Watt announced that Western Australia's live sheep export trade would end from 1 May 2028.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] While RSPCA Australia welcomed the move, the policy announcement was condemned by Nationals leader David Littleproud, Western Australian opposition leader Shane Love, National Farmers' Federation CEO Tony Maher and WA Livestock president Geoff Pearson.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Western Australian Premier Roger Cook also criticised the Government's support package for farmers as insufficient.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In late May 2024, the Western Australian agricultural sector launched a "Keep the Sheep" campaign in opposition to the federal government's decision to end live sheep exports by 2028.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Campaigners staged a large protest rally in Perth, which disrupted traffic.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Following the 2022 New South Wales floods in July 2022, the government announced one-off, non-means tested disaster relief payments to persons living in 29 local government areas impacted by the disaster.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 12 July 2022, Albanese announced a further $80 million to assist with clean-up efforts as well as grants for farmers, small businesses, not-for-profit organisations and local councils.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese also announced $36 million for a program to assess buildings and flooded properties including free demolition of those found to be unlivable.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Following the 2022 south eastern Australia floods, the federal government made a one-off, non-means tested disaster recovery payment of $1,000 per eligible adult and $400 per eligible child available.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Across the states suffering in the crisis, 23 local government areas were made eligible.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 10 January 2024, Albanese announced that the federal government would provide support to victims of the Murchison flooding.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The Australian government also assisted with efforts to reopen Port Vila's airport.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The Royal Australian Air Force evacuated 148 Australian citizens from Vanuatu.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 17 November 2024, the Albanese government confirmed that it would mandate that businesses be required to accept cash payments for essential items from 2026 to ensure that Australians who rely on cash including during natural disasters or digital outages can continue to make purchases.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Tony Burke was appointed Leader of the House in the Albanese ministry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Prior to being sworn in, Burke said that he was determined to "fix" parliamentary procedures and noted that the situation had become a "farce" during the previous Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 24 June 2022, Prime Minister Albanese decided to cut crossbench advisory staff from 4 to the pre-Coalition level of 1.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This decision worsened the government's relations with the Senate crossbench and the Teal independents, with many crossbench Parliamentarians later having their staff allocations increased after making direct appeals to Albanese.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 7 July 2022, Albanese unveiled a new ministerial code of conduct which prohibited ministers from utilising blind trusts.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This was in response to the blind trust used by Christian Porter under the previous government to fund personal defamation proceedings brought by him.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Bell found that Morrison's appointments were corrosive of public trust in government and recommended the implementation of legislation requiring the public announcement of ministerial appointments.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese confirmed that he would recommend that his cabinet implement all of Bell's recommendations in this regard and Burke successfully moved a motion in the House censuring Morrison on 30 November 2022, making him the first former prime minister to be censured.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 30 August 2024, Albanese confirmed during an interview with ABC Radio Melbourne that the 2026 Australian census would include a question relating to sexuality and gender identity, reversing an earlier statement that his government had abandoned the proposal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The following day, Albanese denied that the federal government had revised its policy regarding the inclusion of a gender identity and sexuality question in the upcoming 2026 census.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 8 September, federal treasurer Jim Chalmers confirmed that the 2026 census would include questions about sexual orientation and gender.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Kristy McBain was appointed Minister for the Territories.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In June 2022, she confirmed that the government intended to introduce a bill to give the Northern Territory and the Australian Capital Territory the right to enact their own voluntary-assisted dying laws.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] However, she noted that the government had no plans to expand the number of senators representing the Australian Capital Territory despite its rapidly expanding population.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 1 December 2022, the government's bill to empower the Territories to make laws relating to voluntary-assisted dying passed the Parliament.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Matt Thistlethwaite was appointed the first Assistant Minister for the Republic on 1 June 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Thistlethwaite confirmed that the government's priority during its first term would be to seek constitutional recognition of Indigenous Australians, but that a transition to a republic could be on the agenda for a potential second term.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Following the death of Queen Elizabeth II on 8 September 2022, Albanese reiterated that his government would not pursue becoming a republic during their first parliamentary term.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In July 2024, the role of Assistant Minister for the Republic was abolished.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese later confirmed a republic referendum will not be held during his prime ministership.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 16 December 2022, the Albanese government removed a Morrison government requirement for local councils to hold citizenship ceremonies on 26 January, Australia Day.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 18 January 2023, the Albanese government removed a Morrison government ban on federal public servants working on Australia Day.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early September 2024, the Albanese government launched its National Gender Equity in Sports Governance Policy to boost the representation of women in governance and leadership positions in Australian sports by creating a financial initiative for sporting bodies to make their boards more equal.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Under the policy, national and state-level sporting bodies across Australia must have an equal split of men and women on their boards by 1 July 2027 or risk having their funding suspended.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This policy was developed in collaboration by the Albanese government, the Australian Sports Commission (ASC), and the various State and Territory Agencies for Sport and Recreation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Penny Wong was sworn in as Minister for Foreign Affairs on 23 May 2022 as part of the interim Albanese ministry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The new Prime Minister and Minister flew to Tokyo almost immediately after being sworn in to attend a Quadrilateral Security Dialogue meeting with fellow world leaders United States President Joe Biden, Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi and Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] At the meeting, Albanese and Wong confirmed that the new government intended to make additional action on climate change a key part of Australia's foreign policy moving forward.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In May 2024, Radio New Zealand reported that the Albanese government had slightly increased Australia's foreign aid budget by four percent, bringing its total 2024–2025 aid to A$4.961 billion budget.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In August 2023, the Government had released its new international development strategy, which promised new country, gender, disability and humanitarian aid strategies.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 12 June 2022, Deputy Prime Minister and Defence Minister Richard Marles held a meeting with Chinese Defence Minister Wei Fenghe at the Shangri-La Dialogue in Singapore.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] It was the highest-level contact between Australia and China in almost three years following a deterioration in Australia-China relations under the previous Morrison government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The two ministers discussed an incident involving the Chinese interception of a Royal Australian Air Force Boeing P-8 Poseidon over the South China Sea and political developments in the Pacific Islands.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Earlier, Marles reiterated his government's commitment to pursuing a "productive relationship" with China while advancing its own national interests and regional security within a rules-based system.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In response to Chinese concerns that AUKUS was a "mini-NATO", Marles stated that AUKUS was not an alliance similar to NATO but rather focused on the "sharing and development of capabilities" between Australia, the United Kingdom, and United States.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In November 2022, Albanese held a bilateral meeting with General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party Xi Jinping, bringing an end to the longest diplomatic freeze in 50 years between Australia and China.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In December 2022, Australian Foreign Minister Penny Wong visited China, the first Australian minister to visit the country since 2019, where she met Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early 2023, China ended its unofficial ban on imports of Australian coal, with all restrictions reportedly being lifted by 14 March.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 11 April the countries announced that they reached an agreement over disputes over China's barley imports from Australia, with China agreeing to review its tariffs in exchange for Australia suspending a case against China in the World Trade Organization WTO.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] These developments were followed by Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Ma Zhaoxu's visit to Australia in mid-April 2023 and Australia Minister for Trade and Tourism Don Farrell's visit to Beijing, which marked the first visits by senior Chinese and Australian visits since 2017 and 2019 respectively.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Chinese ambassador to Australia Xiao Qian announced on 18 May that China would allow imports of Australian timber, which was suspended in 2020.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This was followed by the ending of China's 80% tariff on Australian barley in early August 2023 and its tariffs on Australian wine in March 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In September 2023, the Australian and Chinese governments held a high-level dialogue in Beijing, the first in three years, with former trade minister Craig Emerson leading the Australian delegation, while China was represented by former foreign minister Li Zhaoxing.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Later that month Albanese met with Chinese Premier Li Qiang on the sidelines of the East Asia Summit held in Jakarta.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 11 October 2023, Australian journalist Cheng Lei, a former CGTN news anchor who was detained in September 2020, was released and returned to Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] During 4–7 November 2023, Albanese visited Shanghai and Beijing, becoming the first Australian prime minister to visit China in seven years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The trip, described as an effort to improve Australian-Chinese bilateral relations, coincided with the 50th anniversary of Prime Minister Gough Whitlam's first state visit to China.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] During the trip he gave a speech at the China International Import Expo, and met with Premier Li Qiang and CCP General Secretary Xi Jinping.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In mid-June 2024 Albanese hosted Chinese Premier Li Qiang during his state visit to Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] China agreed to extend visa-free access to Australians visiting China for up to 15 days.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The two governments also agreed to provide reciprocal five-year multiple entry visas for tourism, business and visiting family members.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In addition, the two governments agreed to hold talks on improving bilateral military relations to avoid incidents such as the 2023 sonar attack on divers from HMAS *Toowoomba*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Despite a largely productive visit, an incident occurred when Chinese officials attempted to obstruct Cheng Lei, who had since become a Sky News Australia journalist.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 13 February 2025, the Australian Defence Department lodged a formal complaint with the People's Liberation Army following an incident in the South China Sea on 11 February in which a Chinese fighter jet released flares within 30 metres of an RAAF P-8 Poseidon aircraft.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 20 February, the Australian and New Zealand Defence Ministers Marles and Judith Collins confirmed that the Australian and New Zealand militaries were monitoring three Chinese warships that were sailing through Australia's exclusive economic zone near Sydney.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 10 April 2025, Albanese and Marles declined Chinese Ambassador to Australia Xiao Qian's invitation for Australia to join Beijing in opposing US President Donald Trump's international tariffs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese said that "Australians would speak for ourselves" while Marles said that Australia "would not be holding China's hand".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 11 June 2022, Albanese announced that the French defence contractor Naval Group had agreed to settle the previous Morrison government's 2021 cancellation of the 12 attack-class submarines for a €555 million (AU$830 million) compensation settlement.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In response, French Armed Forces Minister Sébastien Lecornu welcomed the settlement and stated that France aims to rebuild its relationship with Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Later that month, Albanese met with French President Emmanuel Macron in France.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 1 July 2022, Albanese travelled to Ukraine to meet with Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy, making him the first Australian Prime Minister to make a diplomatic visit to Ukraine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese pledged a further $100 million in aid to assist with the ongoing Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In addition, Albanese and the Australian delegation visited Kyiv and Bucha on 4 July 2022, which had seen fighting with Russian forces.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early December 2022, Albanese hosted Finnish Prime Minister Sanna Marin in Sydney; which marked the first state visit by a Finnish head of government to Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] During the visit, the two leaders discussed several issues including the Australia-European Union trade agreement, human rights, the Russian invasion of Ukraine, and climate change mitigation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early May 2023, Albanese and Governor-General David Hurley attended the coronation of Charles III in London.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] A cannon salute was also held in Australia to mark the occasion.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early July 2023, Albanese visited Germany ahead of the NATO summit in Lithuania.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Prior to a scheduled meeting with German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, Albanese confirmed a bilateral deal to sell Australian-made armoured vehicles to Germany.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In July 2024, Deputy Prime Minister Marles announced a further $250 million in military assistance, the largest single military package from Australia to Ukraine since the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In late December 2024, the federal government confirmed it was working to locate 32-year-old Australian man Oscar Jenkins after he appeared in a video on pro-Kremlin social media accounts purportedly showing him being detained and questioned by Russian soldiers in Ukraine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Jenkins had been serving in the Ukrainian armed forces.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In mid-January 2025, Albanese promised to take "the strongest action possible" against Russia if it could be verified that the Russian military had executed Jenkins.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese visited India between 8 and 11 March, where he met Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi for the Australia-India Annual Leaders' Summit in New Delhi.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The state visit focused on bilateral trade and investment, renewable energy, technology, defence and security cooperation, and educational and cultural ties.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Australia and India had previously signed the Australia-India Economic Cooperation and Trade Agreement, which came into force on 29 December 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] During the visit, Albanese and Modi attended the fourth Australia-India cricket test at Narendra Modi Stadium in Ahmedabad, where the two leaders also rode a chariot in a lap of honour.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Modi reciprocated with a two-day state visit to Sydney on 22 May 2023 where he met Australian political and business leaders including Albanese.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In October 2022, the Albanese government reversed the previous Morrison government's decision to recognise West Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Foreign Minister Penny Wong reaffirmed that Jerusalem's status should be decided through peace negotiations between Israelis and Palestinians.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In August 2023, Wong confirmed that Australia would revert to its pre-2014 policy of designating the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Gaza Strip as "Occupied Palestinian Territories" and the Israeli settlements there as "illegal".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Following the outbreak of the Gaza war on 7 October 2023, the Albanese government defended Israel's right to defend itself and retaliate against Hamas' attack.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Wong also called for the release of hostages taken by Hamas.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Despite its support for Israel, the Albanese government declined to supply weapons to Israel since the start of the conflict.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In mid-February 2024, Wong expressed concerns about Israel's planned Rafah offensive, describing it as "unjustifiable".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese, along with Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and New Zealand Prime Minister Christopher Luxon, subsequently issued a joint statement expressing concerns over the planned Israeli ground offensive.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early April 2024, Wong said that the federal government was considering recognising Palestinian statehood as a means of facilitating a two-state solution for Israel and Palestine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Her comments attracted criticism from the Executive Council of Australian Jewry President Daniel Aghon and was welcomed by the president of the Australia Palestine Advocacy Network, Nasser Mashni.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In May 2024, the Albanese government voted in favour of a United Nations General Assembly resolution that determined that Palestine met the requirements for United Nations membership.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Wong subsequently confirmed that the vote did not mean that Australia would recognise Palestinian statehood but was rather about extending "modest additional rights to participate in United Nations forums".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] She reiterated that Australia would only recognise Palestine "when we think the time is right" and that a reformed Palestinian Authority, not Hamas, should "lead its people" in a future Palestinian state.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 1 October 2024, Albanese and Opposition leader Peter Dutton condemned memorial services held at several Shiite Muslim mosques in Sydney to commemorate the death of leader of the terrorist group Hezbollah, Hassan Nasrallah.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In addition, federal police commissioner Reece Kershaw warned that law enforcement authorities would take action against those displaying Hezbollah or Hamas flags at national pro-Palestinian rallies being held on 6 October to mark the first anniversary of the 2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 21 November 2024, the International Criminal Court (ICC) issued arrest warrants for Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Defense Minister Yoav Gallant, and Hamas military commander Mohammed Deif (who was subsequently confirmed to have been killed).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Foreign Minister Penny Wong stated in an X post that the Australian government "respects the independence of the ICC and its important role in upholding international law".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 10 June 2022, Albanese hosted New Zealand Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern on her first official visit to Australia since 2020.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The two leaders discussed a range of issues including Australia's controversial Section 501 deportation policy (which had disproportionately affected New Zealanders living in Australia), growing Chinese influence in the Pacific Islands, climate change, and working with Pacific neighbours.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 7 February 2023, Albanese hosted his New Zealand counterpart Chris Hipkins, who had succeeded Ardern in late January 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Besides reaffirming Australian-New Zealand bilateral relations, they also discussed the controversial Section 501 deportation policy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese reiterated that his government would revise the deportation policy to take into account individuals' connections to Australia and the length of time they had lived in the country.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Immigration Minister Andrew Giles also issued Ministerial Directive 99 requiring Australian immigration officials to consider a non-citizen's community ties and length of time spent in Australia when cancelling a visa.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This policy change was welcomed by Hipkins and the New Zealand Government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 22 April 2023, Albanese, Home Affairs Minister Clare O'Neil, and Giles announced the creation of a new direct pathway to Australian citizenship for New Zealand Special Category Visa (SCV) holders, commencing 1 July 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Under the policy, SCV holders who have resided in Australia for at least four years and met other residency requirements will be eligible to apply for Australian citizenship without having to apply for permanent residency.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In addition, children born in Australia to a New Zealand citizen from 1 July will automatically be eligible for Australian citizenship.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The announcement was welcomed by NZ Prime Minister Hipkins and Oz Kiwi chairperson Joanne Cox for improving New Zealanders' access to Australian citizenship, health and social security services.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 26 July 2023, Albanese met with Hipkins as part of the annual Australia-New Zealand leaders' meeting.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early February 2024, Foreign Minister Wong and Defence Minister Marles hosted their New Zealand counterparts Winston Peters and Judith Collins for a joint bilateral meeting of foreign and defence ministers in Melbourne.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Marles confirmed that Australia would send officials to brief their New Zealand counterparts about AUKUS Pillar Two, which would focus on advanced military technology including quantum computing and artificial intelligence.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] New Zealand is not expected to join AUKUS Pillar One due to its nuclear-free policy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The two governments also committed to reinforced security cooperation in the Indo-Pacific and increased military integration between the Australian and New Zealand militaries.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In May 2024, following criticism from opposition politicians that Ministerial Directive 99 had allowed several non-citizens convicted of serious crimes to remain in Australia, Albanese and Giles confirmed that the immigration directive would be revised.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 7 June 2024, Giles issued "Directive 110", which clarified that non-citizens convicted of serious crimes could be deported despite living their whole lives in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In response, New Zealand Prime Minister Christopher Luxon expressed concern that people with little or no connection with New Zealand were being deported back to the country.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 12 January 2023, Albanese became the first foreign leader to address the National Parliament of Papua New Guinea.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] That same day, he and Papua New Guinea Prime Minister James Marape signed a joint statement pledging that the two countries would reach a new security deal by late April 2023.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In mid-June 2024, several Australian cabinet ministers including Marles, Wong and Pat Conroy attended the 30th Australia-Papua New Guinea Ministerial Forum in Port Moresby.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] During the visit, the Albanese government announced several initiatives under a bilateral security agreement with PNG.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This was followed on 12 December 2024 with the announcement that Australia would fund the addition of a PNG team to the National Rugby League from 2028.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] As part of the funding deal, PNG agreed that Australia would remains its "security partner of choice" and PNG would not sign a military or police security deal with China.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In late September 2023, Defence Minister Richard Marles announced that 500 Australian troops would be relocated to Townsville over the course of six years from 2025 to strengthen the Australian Army's ability to conduct operations missions in the Pacific.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This announcement was criticised by the city's mayor Jenny Hill who claimed that Townsville City Council was not consulted about military personnel's housing.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early November 2023, Albanese attended the Pacific Islands Forum annual meeting in the Cook Islands where he met several leaders including Tuvalan Prime Minister Kausea Natano.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Key issues discussed at the meeting included the impact of Australian carbon emissions, climate change, nuclear safety, and ongoing US-China tensions.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 10 November 2023, Albanese and Natano signed a bilateral pact between Australia and Tuvalu, known as the Falepili Union.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Under the terms of the treaty, Tuvalan citizens will be given a "special mobility pathway" that would allow them to live and work in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In addition, Australia will respond to major natural disasters, pandemics or military aggression against Tuvalu.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In return, Australia will have a veto power over Tuvalu's security and defence agreements with other countries.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 28 August 2024, the Albanese government's Pacific Policing Initiative (PPI) won the support of member states of the Pacific Islands Forum, which Australia is a member.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Under the PPI, the Australian federal government will establish a police development and coordination hub in Brisbane for training Pacific police officers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In addition, a "Pacific Police Support Group" will also be established to help with natural disasters, emergencies and other events.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Four police training centres of excellence will also be set up across the Pacific, with Australia contributing about A$400m in infrastructure funding over five years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Albanese described the launch of the Pacific Police Initiative as a "great outcome" for Pacific security.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Melanesian Spearhead Group director-general Leonard Louma and Vanuatuan Prime Minister Charlot Salwai expressed concern that the PPI could be used by Australian and New Zealand to serve Western interests and lock China out of the region.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] By contrast, Tongan Prime Minister Siaosi Sovaleni, Fijian Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka, Tuvalan Prime Minister Feleti Teo, and New Zealand Prime Minister Christopher Luxon expressed support for the PPI.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Solomon Islands Prime Minister Jeremiah Manele expressed cautious support for the Pacific Police Initiative but said that national consultation was important.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 20 December 2024, Albanese signed an A$190 million (US$118 million) agreement with Solomon Islands Prime Minister Manele to expand the capabilities of the Royal Solomon Islands Police Force.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] This funding package would support the Solomon Islands Police Force's funding, training and infrastructure including the construction of a new police training centre in Honiara.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] According to Agence France-Presse and Reuters, this funding packaged was intended to compete with expanding Chinese influence in the Pacific region particularly the Solomon Islands, which had entered into a security agreement with China in 2022.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 6 June 2022, Albanese along with Foreign Minister Wong, Trade Minister Don Farrell and Industry Minister Ed Husic visited Indonesian President Joko Widodo in Jakarta to reaffirm relations with Indonesia and ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 3 July 2023, Albanese hosted Indonesian President Widodo during a 36-hour visit to Sydney, where he also met several Australian business and political leaders.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 6 September 2023, Albanese attended the ASEAN Summit in Jakarta to promote trade relations with the region.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 8 September, Albanese met with Philippine President Bongbong Marcos in Manila, marking the first state visit to the Philippines by an Australian Prime Minister in two decades.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The two governments agreed to conduct joint naval patrols in the South China Sea.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] During 4–6 March 2024, Australia hosted a "special summit" between Australia and the member nations of ASEAN to mark 50 years of diplomatic dialogue relations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Several diplomatic and economic initiatives were reached at the summit, including a $2 billion "Southeast Asia Investment Financing Facility", a $140 million infrastructure development partnership, and expanded business visa programs.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 15 December 2024 Albanese, Wong and Burke confirmed that surviving Bali Nine members Matthew Norman, Scott Rush, Martin Stephens, Si Yi Chen, and Michael Czugaj had been repatriated to Australia after serving over 19 years in prison in Indonesia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] The five had been convicted of attempting to import over eight kilograms of heroin from Bali in 2005.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In late October 2023, Albanese undertook a four-day state visit to Washington, D.C., where he met United States President Joe Biden, Australian Ambassador to the United States Kevin Rudd and several members of the United States Congress.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Key objectives of the visit including lobbying Congress to pass AUKUS-related legislation, sign new deals on critical minerals and discuss issues with China and the Israel-Hamas War.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 14 December 2023, Congress passed legislation allowing nuclear-powered submarines to be sold to Australia under the AUKUS agreement.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 21 September 2024, Albanese met with Biden ahead of the annual Quadrilateral Security Dialogue meeting in Wilmington, Delaware.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Following the 2024 United States presidential election held on 6 November, Albanese and Opposition leader Dutton congratulated Republican Party candidate and President-elect Donald Trump.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 29 September 2023, Marles announced that the Australian Defence Force would be retiring its fleet of MRH-90 Taipan helicopters following a fatal crash during Exercise Talisman Sabre in July 2023 which killed four military personnel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In early January 2024, Albanese ordered an inquiry into whether the previous Morrison government had failed to hand over documents relating to Australia's involvement in the 2003 invasion of Iraq to the National Archives in 2020 for public release.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] On 12 September 2024, Marles stripped nine commanding officers who served in the War in Afghanistan of their distinguished service medals, implementing the final recommendation of the Brereton Report which had found "credible evidence" that Australian soldiers had unlawfully killed 39 people.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] In late March 2025, Reuters reported that Albanese had pledged A$74 billion for missile procurement in 2024, which included A$21 billion to establish a Guided Weapons and Explosive Ordnance Enterprise in Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Australia has formed partnerships with companies like Lockheed Martin, Kongsberg, and Raytheon to acquire long-range strike and hypersonic missiles, with a focus on enhancing defense capabilities in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Despite global supply shortages, local production of missiles, including Kongsberg's Joint Strike and Naval Strike Missiles, is set to begin in 2027, with 10 Australian suppliers already contracted.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p03] Australia is also working to produce Guided Multiple Launch Rocket Systems (GMLRS) and High Mobility Artillery Rocket Systems (HIMARS) locally, aimed at improving regional defense readiness.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In a landslide victory and historic comeback, having overturned most of the opinion polling showing either a smaller majority for the Labor government or a hung parliament, the Labor Party won a second majority government in the 2025 election.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In doing so, Albanese became the first prime minister since 2004 to win a second consecutive term, as well as the first Labor leader to win re-election since Bob Hawke in 1990.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Following the 2025 Bondi Beach shooting on 14 December which targeted a Hanukah gathering, Albanese vowed to "eradicate" antisemitism in Australia and announced plans to introduce new tougher gun laws limiting the number of weapons.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 15 December, the National Cabinet unanimously agreed to strengthen gun laws.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 19 December, the Albanese government also confirmed plans to launch a gun buyback program.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 18 December, the Albanese government confirmed that they would adopt all the recommendations of the government's special envoy to combat antisemitism Jillian Segal's "Plan to Combat Antisemitism".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 21 December, Albanese announced an Independent Commonwealth Review into Australia's federal law enforcement and intelligence agencies to be led by retired public servant Dennis Richardson.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The review was expected to deliver a public report on the attack by late April 2026.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 29 December, the review's terms of reference were released.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The Albanese government initially ruled out holding a federal royal commission into the Bondi Beach shootings, with Home Affairs Minister Tony Burke saying that it was not the best format for national security issues.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] However, by 8 January 2026, mounting political and public pressure resulted in the establishment of the Royal Commission on Antisemitism and Social Cohesion, that incorporated the Richardson review, to report by 14 December 2026.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 12 January 2026, Albanese announced that the Australian Parliament would reconvene on 19 January to introduce fast-tracked hate speech and firearms legislation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] He confirmed that the Labor federal government would seek cross-party support from the Coalition and Australian Greens.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The bill passed both houses of parliament on 20 January 2026, It passed in the House 116 votes to 7, and 38-22 in the Senate.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] As of May 2026, there is a constitutional challenge from the National Socialist Network related to the constitutionality of the 2026 hate speech and hate group legislation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Following the 2025 New South Wales floods in May 2025, Emergency Minister Kristy McBain announced on 22 May that the Australian Defence Force personnel would be deployed for search and rescue operations in Taree.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] By 24 May, the National Emergency Management Agency was working to restore food supply, telecommunications and power to flood-affected communities.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 31 July 2025, the Albanese government passed legislation in the Australian Parliament reducing student loan debt by 20 percent.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The Universities Accord Bill covers several university and TAFE student loans including the Higher Education Loan Programme, VET Student Loan and the Australian Apprenticeship Support Loan.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In mid November 2025, *The Guardian Australia* reported that the Australian Skills Quality Authority (ASQA) had cancelled the registrations of 11 vocational training organisations and voided about 30,000 diplomas, certificates and statements of attainment since late 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The ASQA also deregistered four educational providers and investigated 144 other providers for "serious matters".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In 2023, the Albanese government had allocated A$37.8 million to improving the quality of vocational training and educational programmes, including establishing a new enforcement unit at the ASQA and a new tip line.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] This crackdown was part of the federal government's ongoing efforts to combat unscrupulous vocational diploma mills providing dubious courses, accreditation, and so-called "fast-track skilled migration pathways".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 30 March 2026, Albanese confirmed that the Australian government would reduce the fuel excise rate from 52.6 cents to 26.3 cents per litre between 1 April and 30 June to address rising fuel prices caused by the 2026 Iran war, and encourage people to use public transportation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] State and federal leaders also agreed to reduce the heavy vehicle road user charge during that period to help truck drivers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In April 2026, Albanese announced that the government would introduce a cap of three gambling advertisements per hour and prohibit gambling advertising on sports jerseys.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Ads will be capped from 6:30 am to 8:30 pm and will be banned during school pick up and drop off times.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Gambling ads will also be banned on social media unless users are over 18 and are able to opt out of these notifications.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Gambling ads featuring celebrities or athletes will also be banned.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Ads containing odds details will also be banned.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Gambling ads at sports venues will also be banned.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 4 March 2026, the Albanese government launched a federal parliamentary inquiry into racism, hate and violence against Indigenous Australians in response to the 2026 Invasion Day protest bombing attempt, which occurred in Perth on Australia Day.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In late July 2025, Google warned that it would sue the Australian government if YouTube was included under the government's social media ban for children below 16 years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 30 July, the Albanese government that it would extend its social media age limit to include YouTube following advice from eSafety commissioner Julie Inman Grant.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 10 December 2025, the Online Safety Amendment (Social Media Minimum Age) Act 2024 came into effect, requiring social media to implement age verification systems with the goal of restricting access to minors under the age of 16.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 31 March, Communications Minister Anika Wells announced that the government would investigate social media platforms Facebook, Instagram, Snapchat, TikTok and YouTube for potential violations of the under-16 social media ban.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In July 2025, Albanese went on a six-day visit to China.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The visit include a trip to the Great Wall and a panda breeding center, which drew criticism from the Coalition.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Albanese responded by saying that the visits were intended to show respect to China.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] According to critics, Albanese ignored the issue of human rights in China, including human rights violations in Hong Kong, Xinjiang, and Tibet, and focused only on trade.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 4 May 2026, Albanese and Japanese Prime Minister Takaichi Sanae signed four agreements in Canberra to boost bilateral cooperation in the areas of energy, defence and critical minerals and a joint declaration on economic security cooperation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The critical minerals agreement identifies six rare earth strategic projects to diversify supply chains including the Lynas rare earth project in Kalgoorlie and Alcoa's Gallium Recovery Project.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 23 March 2026, Albanese and the President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen signed a free trade agreement following eight years of negotiations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The two leaders also announced a new defence partnership between Australia and the European Union.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In May 2025, Albanese echoed criticisms from other Western nations in demanding Israel allow the supply of humanitarian aid into the Gaza Strip, condemning Israel's actions as "completely unacceptable" and an "outrage".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] However, he opposed sanctions against Israel over the blockade of Gaza, saying he was focusing on "peace and security for both Israelis and Palestinians" rather than "soundbites".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The joint travel bans and sanctions were condemned by Israeli Foreign Minister Gideon Sa'ar, United States Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Ben-Gvir and Smotrich as hostile actions against Israel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Albanese defended his government's response, stating that Australia was concerned about humanitarian issues in Gaza.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The Coalition's foreign affairs spokesperson Michaelia Cash expressed concern about the travel ban being part of a "pattern of decisions by the Albanese government targeting the Israeli government".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In late July 2025, the Albanese government joined 15 other countries including France, Canada and New Zealand in signing the "New York Call" which proposed recognising Palestinian statehood at the United Nations General Assembly in September 2025.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] This announcement was criticised by both the US and Israeli governments for "rewarding" Hamas' terrorism.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 9 August, Foreign Minister Wong joined her German, Italian, New Zealand and British counterparts in issuing a joint statement condemning Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's plan to militarily occupy Gaza City.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] That same day, Albanese and New Zealand Prime Minister Christopher Luxon called for a ceasefire in Gaza and opposed Israeli plans to occupy Gaza City.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 11 August 2025, Albanese announced plans to recognise the State of Palestine at the United Nations in September.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In August 2025, the Greens urged the Albanese government to impose direct sanctions on high-ranking members of Netanyahu's government and to stop supplying parts for F-35 fighter jets to the global supply chain that can be accessed by Israel.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Greens senator David Shoebridge said: "If the Albanese government stopped the export of F-35 fighter jet parts to Israel, then their F-35 fleet would be grounded." According to Amnesty International, by participating in the production of the F-35, Australia violated the Arms Trade Treaty.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In June 2025, Albanese and Foreign Minister Wong voiced support for US strikes on Iranian nuclear sites.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Albanese also confirmed that Australia had withdrawn its diplomats from Tehran and would designate the IRGC as a terrorist organisation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Wong said that this was the first time since World War II that Australia had expelled an ambassador.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 21 October 2025, the office of the Attorney-General issued a provisional transparency notice designating the Iranian state media outlet Press TV as a foreign government entity.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The designation was finalised on 18 November 2025, and was formally listed on the Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme register.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 27 November 2025, the Australian Parliament formally designated the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps as a state sponsor of terrorism, under the framework of the Criminal Code Amendment (State Sponsors of Terrorism) Act 2025.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] During the 2025-2026 Iranian protests, the Australian embassy in Iran ceased its operations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Australian citizens were urged by the government to leave Iran as soon as possible due to the violent crackdowns and arrests by Iranian security forces.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Following the outbreak of the 2026 Iran war on 28 February 2026, Albanese along with Wong and Marles expressed support for US and Israeli strikes, also stating Australia stood with "the brave people of Iran in their struggle against oppression".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Two more Iranian footballers subsequently sought asylum in Australia, bringing the total number to seven.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] That same day, Albanese confirmed that Australia would deploy a long-range reconnaissance aircraft and air-to-air missiles to the United Arab Emirates to help the Gulf States defend themselves against Iranian missiles.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In early December 2025, *The Guardian Australia* reported that the Albanese government had declined an American offer to help repatriate about 40 Australian citizens from camps near the Syrian-Turkish border including Roj camp.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] These individuals are the wives, widows and children of dead and imprisoned Islamic State fighters.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In June 2025, Home Affairs Minister Tony Burke had met with Save the Children CEO Mat Tinkler and repatriate advocate Kamalle Dabboussy, who expressed concerns that these individuals were being radicalised.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In August 2025, Tinkler and Dabboussy confirmed that the US government had offered to facilitate the repatriation of the 40 Australians.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] While the Australian government has previously repatriated several nationals from Syria in 2019 and 2022, the Albanese government had declined the American offer due to concerns of a backlash from certain constituents during the lead-up to the 2025 Australian federal election.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In mid-February 2026, a group of 34 Australian nationals including 11 women and 23 children, had left the Al-Roj refugee camp with the intention of traveling to Damascus to return to Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] They had been blocked from leaving Syrian Democratic Forces-controlled territory by Syrian government forces.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Opposition Liberal Senator Sarah Henderson advocated blocking the return of ISIS-linked adults, citing public safety concerns.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In late April 2026, a group of four Australian women and nine children left the Al-Roj refugee camp and headed to Damascus with the intention of returning to Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] According to a Syrian official, their repatriation had been delayed by the Australian government for two weeks while they "put procedures in place" to receive the repatriates.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 6 May, the Albanese government confirmed that the group had booked tickets and were expected to arrive in Australia the following day.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The group arrived at Sydney and Melbourne Airports on 7 May.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Police charged two of the women in Melbourne with crime against humanity relating to slavery while a third woman who arrived in Sydney was charged with entering a prohibited area and bineg a member of a terrorist organisation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 15 May 2025, Albanese visited Indonesian President Prabowo Subianto in Jakarta, making his first overseas trip following the 2025 federal election.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The state visit sought to shore up Australia–Indonesia relations in the areas of food security, energy, trade, and critical minerals as well as personal relations between the two national leaders.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Albanese received an official state reception from Subianto at Merdeka Palace in Jakarta.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] During the visit, Albanese encouraged Indonesia to pursue closer defence cooperation with Australia while Subianto encouraged Australian investment in the Indonesian economy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Albanese also stated that Indonesia had ruled out allowing the Russians to establish a military base in Western New Guinea.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In mid November 2025, Albanese hosted President Prabowo during his first state visit to Sydney.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 12 November, the two leaders confirmed that they would sign a new defence treaty in January 2026 that would commit the two governments to consulting on both leadership and ministerial levels on security matters.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The treaty builds upon the 2024 Defence Cooperation Agreement, and is also based on a cancelled 1995 bilateral peace agreement signed between Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating and Indonesian President Suharto.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Albanese and Prabowo formally signed the bilateral security treaty on 6 February 2026.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In April 2026, Albanese visited Singapore, Brunei and Malaysia to strengthen economic and energy cooperation with those countries in response to energy shortages caused by the 2026 Iran war.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In return for obtain for obtaining access to fuel and fertiliser from Malaysia and Brunei, Australian has agreed supply gas and food.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 10 April, Albanese met with Singaporean Prime Minister Lawrence Wong and signed a bilateral agreement to meet each other's energy needs, with Singapore agreeing to continue supplying refined fuel in return for Australia supplying liquefied natural gas (LNG).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 15 April, Albanese met with Sultan of Brunei Hassanal Bolkiah and the two leaders signed an agreement to maintain open trade and to protect energy supply chains particularly Bruneian diesel and fertiliser exports to Australia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 16 April, Albanese met with Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The Malaysian oil and gas company Petronas agreed to provide Australia with excess fuel supplies in return for Australia prioritising its LNG exports to Malaysia.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Between 9 and 10 August 2025, Albanese visited New Zealand Prime Minister Christopher Luxon in Queenstown for an annual bilateral head of government meeting.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] During the visit, the two heads of government reiterated calls for a ceasefire in the Gaza war and condemned Israel's plan to occupy Gaza City.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The two heads of government also discussed various bilateral trade and defence issues including the Gaza war, relations with China and Australia's 501 deportation policy.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The two leaders also laid wreaths at a memorial to fallen ANZAC soldiers in Arrowtown on 10 August.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In early December 2025, Treasurer Jim Chalmers and Minister for Climate Change and Energy Chris Bowen met with their New Zealand counterparts Nicola Willis and Simon Watts to discuss strengthening bilateral cooperation on climate action, clean energy and related regulations.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The four ministers issued a joint statement reaffirming bilateral cooperation in the Pacific and global security challenges, and criticising Chinese assertiveness in the South China Sea and Russian aggression against Ukraine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In response, the Chinese Embassy in New Zealand criticised the New Zealand and Australian governments for interfering in Chinese internal affairs, their perceived silence on US military actions during the 2026 Iran war and their alleged "poor records" on human rights and ethnic minorities.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 29 August 2025, the Australian and Nauruan governments signed an agreement with Nauru agreeing to accept several formerly detained people without valid Australian visas to the islands in exchange for financial compensation of at least A$408 million.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 14 September 2025, the Australian and Papuan governments announced plans to sign a landmark defence treaty that would integrate the two countries' defence forces on 15 September, which would coincide with the 50th anniversary of Papua New Guinea's independence.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] This proposed agreement would allow Australians and Papuans to serve in each other's militaries, allowing Papuans to gain Australian citizenship.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 16 September, Albanese said that Australia would contribute funds to the construction of a new ministerial wing for the National Parliament of Papua New Guinea.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] By 18 September, the two governments had still not yet signed the defence treaty after Papuan Prime Minister James Marape's cabinet was unable to reach a quorum.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Instead, the Australian and Papuan governments signed a communique and committed to signing the treaty within the following weeks.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 19 September, the Chinese Embassy in Papua New Guinea expressed concern that the Australian-Papuan defence treaty would affect Papua New Guinea's ability to conduct foreign relations with third parties.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The Papua New Guinea cabinet subsequently approved the treaty on 2 October.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Marape and Albanese signed the treaty in Canberra on 6 October 2025.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 29 June 2026, Albanese and Vanuatuan Prime Minister Jotham Napat signed a bilateral economic and security agreement barring the establishment of any foreign military base on the island state.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 25 July 2025, Agriculture Minister Julie Collins confirmed that Australia would relax biosecurity restrictions on US beef imports.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] This announcement was welcomed by both US President Donald Trump and Secretary of Agriculture Brooke L.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Rollins as a "major trade breakthrough" for US beef exporters.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 21 October 2025, Albanese met with Trump at the White House.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The two leaders signed a rare earths agreement aimed at countering Chinese control over the supply of critical minerals.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Trump also reiterated the United States' commitment to supplying nuclear-powered submarines to Australia as part of the AUKUS agreement.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] During the White House visit, Trump rebuked Australian Ambassador Kevin Rudd for making critical social media remarks about him in the past.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] Following the press conference, Rudd personally apologised to Trump.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] While Albanese and veteran Republican Michael McCaul expressed confidence in Ambassador Rudd, Opposition Leader Sussan Ley called on Rudd to resign as Ambassador to the United States.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In late December 2025, Foreign Minister Penny Wong voiced support for US airstrikes against Islamic State forces in Nigeria that occurred on Christmas Day.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In January 2026, Albanese called for "dialogue and diplomacy" following a U.S. military operation in Venezuela that resulted in the capture of President Nicolás Maduro.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 13 July 2025, Minister for Defence Industry Pat Conroy stated that Australia would not commit military forces to any conflict involving Taiwan during an interview with the Australian Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The previous day, the *Financial Times* had reported that Elbridge Colby, the Under Secretary of Defense for Policy, had been pressing Australian and Japanese officials on what they would do in the event of a conflict between China and Taiwan.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In response, the Shadow Defence Minister Angus Taylor said that Australia should make "principled commitments to Taiwan's security and be prepared to act under certain circumstances".
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 26 July 2025, the Australian Foreign and Defence Ministers Wong and Marles signed the Geelong Treaty with their British counterparts, Foreign Secretary David Lammy and Secretary of State for Defence John Healey.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] The Geelong Treaty is a 50-year bilateral defence agreement to facilitate cooperation on the construction of Australia's nuclear-powered SSN-AUKUS submarine fleet under Phase I of the AUKUS pact.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] On 28 May 2026, the Australian government filed a A$2 billion lawsuit against the American multinational conglomerate 3M, alleging that the company made false statements about the long-term environmental impact of firefighting foam containing PFAS that was used at 28 Australian Defence Force sites.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] This lawsuit marks the largest legal claim brought by the Australian government.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/albanese-government-p04] In response, 3M said that it would fight the lawsuit.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The ***Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999*** (Cth) is an act of the Parliament of Australia that provides a framework for protection of the Australian environment, including its biodiversity and its natural and culturally significant places.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] Enacted on 16 July 2000, it established a range of processes to help protect and promote the recovery of threatened species and ecological communities, and preserve significant places from decline.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The act is as of September 2024 administered by the Department of Climate Change, Energy, the Environment and Water.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] Lists of threatened species are drawn up under the act, and these lists, the primary reference to threatened species in Australia, are available online through the Species Profile and Threats Database (SPRAT).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] As an act of the Australian Parliament, it relies for its constitutional validity upon the legislative powers of the Parliament granted by the Australian Constitution, and key provisions of the act are largely based on a number of international, multilateral or bilateral treaties.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] A number of reviews, audits and assessments of the act have found the act deeply flawed and thus not providing adequate environmental protection.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* replaced the *National Parks and Wildlife Conservation Act 1975*, after this legislation was repealed by the *Environmental Reform (Consequential Provisions) Act 1999*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The *Environmental Reform Act* also repealed four other acts: *Environment Protection (Impact of Proposals) Act 1974*; *Endangered Species Protection Act 1992*; *World Heritage Properties Conservation Act 1983*; and the *Whale Protection Act 1980*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] This Act also made consequential changes to other legislation, and various administrative arrangements, required by the new scheme introduced by the act.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The act received royal assent on 16 July 1999 and commenced on 16 July 2000.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Regulations 2000 also commenced on 16 July 2000, (with 21 amendments up to the latest on 17 December 2018).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The purpose of the regulations is to give effect to the provisions of the act.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The legislation has had many amendments through its lifetime.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] On 16 June 2014 the proposed amendments passed the House of Representatives, despite opposition from environmental campaigners and significant legal commentators who criticised the bill and expressed concerns about the delegation of Commonwealth environmental approval powers.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The act established the use of Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Regulations, which have provided for the issuing of approvals and permits for a range of activities on Commonwealth land and land affecting the Commonwealth.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] For example, commercial picking of wildflowers is regulated under the act, and cannot be undertaken without an appropriate permit.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] Failure to comply with the act can result in penalties including remediation of damage, court injunctions, and criminal and civil penalties.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] As of September 2024, the legislation is administered by the Department of Climate Change, Energy, the Environment and Water.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The list must be reviewed every five years, and the government can add new matters to this list by regulation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] "If a proposed action is likely to have a significant impact on any of the areas, it may require Commonwealth approval before it can begin.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] Lists of threatened species, such as threatened fauna, are drawn up under the act and these lists are the primary reference to threatened species in Australia and are available online through the *Species Profile and Threats Database* (SPRAT).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] As an act of the Australian Parliament, it relies for its Constitutional validity upon the legislative powers of the Parliament granted by the Australian Constitution, which does not expressly refer to the environment.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] Significant impacts on MNES trigger assessment under the act.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] A new assessment trigger was added to the act in mid-2013, via the *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Amendment Act 2013*.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The amendment relates to significant impacts on water resources, for example where actions by a large coal mining development, in particular coal seam gas may adversely affect groundwater in the area.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The amendment was introduced by Tony Windsor, an independent Member of Parliament (MP).
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] As of March 2020, the Australian Conservation Foundation is taking the Morrison government to court for failing to apply the water trigger when it assessed Adani's North Galilee Water Scheme, part of its essential infrastructure for the proposed Carmichael coal mine.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The proposed changes do not include the promised prototype national standards.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] On 27 November 2025, the Albanese government struck a deal with the Greens in the Senate that allowed the passage of a new environmental act to replace this legislation.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The new legislation aims to speed up approvals of projects including new energy developments and housing, create a new body called the Environment Protection Authority which can immediately order a business to stop work if it finds a breach of the rules.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The government has also included $300 million to support jobs and maintain modern equipment in the forestry industry.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] The government also removed the exemption for high-risk land clearing and regional forestry agreements.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] A large number of studies, audits, reviews and parliamentary inquiries have examined various aspects of the legislation over the years.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] Section 522A of the act requires that an independent review is conducted every ten years, to examine its operation and the extent to which its objects have been met.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] A 2005 study looked specifically at threatened species recovery.
[src:environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999/environment-protection-and-biodiversity-conservation-act-1999] A review of the act and actions taken under the act was published by the Australian National Audit Office (ANAO) in March 2007, entitled "The Conservation and Protection of National Threatened Species and Ecological Communities".
